const SCENARIOS_AEMT = {

bd_burger: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Burgers — 58-year-old male, chest pain, diaphoretic.", chief_complaint:"Inferior STEMI, chest pressure radiating to jaw", scene_description:"A heavyset male cook sits on a milk crate behind the counter, pale and diaphoretic. He has been having chest pressure for 45 minutes and thought it was heartburn. His coworker finally called when he started sweating through his shirt.", patient_info:"58-year-old male, PMH: hypertension, hyperlipidemia, smoker x30 years.", vitals:{bp:"158/96",hr:"94",rr:"18",spo2:"94%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Substernal crushing pressure 8/10 radiating to left arm and jaw. Diaphoretic and pale. 12-lead shows ST elevation in II, III, aVF — inferior STEMI. Lung sounds clear. SpO2 94% on room air.", teaching_points:"1. AEMT scope includes 12-lead acquisition — recognize inferior STEMI (ST elevation II, III, aVF with reciprocal depression in I and aVL) and activate the cath lab via medical director protocol without delay. 2. Establish IV access en route, administer aspirin 324mg PO if not given, and apply O2 to maintain SpO2 above 94% — get this patient to the cath lab fast." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Burgers — anaphylaxis, female employee, facial swelling, stridor.", chief_complaint:"Anaphylaxis with airway compromise", scene_description:"A 24-year-old waitress is in the break room leaning forward with audible stridor. Her lips and tongue are visibly swollen. She ate a new sauce about 15 minutes ago and is saying she can feel her throat closing.", patient_info:"24-year-old female, PMH: seasonal allergies. No known food allergies.", vitals:{bp:"88/54",hr:"128",rr:"28",spo2:"91%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Angioedema of lips and tongue with audible stridor. Widespread urticaria. Hypotensive and tachycardic. SpO2 91% declining. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Epinephrine 1:1000 0.3mg IM to the lateral thigh is your first intervention — do not delay for IV access when the airway is closing. 2. Establish large bore IV for fluid resuscitation — anaphylactic shock involves massive vasodilation and capillary leak; NS bolus supports blood pressure while epinephrine takes effect." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Burgers — male, 30s, unresponsive in restroom, suspected opioid OD.", chief_complaint:"Opioid overdose, respiratory failure", scene_description:"Male found on the restroom floor unresponsive with a used syringe nearby. He has a faint pulse but agonal respirations. Lips are cyanotic. SpO2 reading 68%.", patient_info:"Approximately 32-year-old male, PMH: unknown. Track marks bilateral arms.", vitals:{bp:"80/46",hr:"48",rr:"4 agonal",spo2:"68%",gcs:"3",temp:"96.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Weak carotid pulse. Agonal respirations. Pinpoint pupils. SpO2 68%. BVM ventilation improving SpO2 slowly. Fentanyl likely given severity of presentation.", teaching_points:"1. At AEMT level you can place a supraglottic airway (King LT or iGel) if BVM ventilation is inadequate — SpO2 of 68% with agonal breathing requires immediate airway intervention beyond positioning alone. 2. Naloxone 2mg IN or IV is appropriate but may be insufficient for fentanyl — be prepared for repeat dosing; naloxone half-life is shorter than fentanyl so the patient can re-narcotize after initial improvement." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Burgers — elderly female, fall in parking lot, hip fracture, IV pain management needed.", chief_complaint:"Hip fracture, severe pain, anticoagulated patient", scene_description:"78-year-old female on the pavement after tripping on a curb. Her right leg is externally rotated and shortened. She is on warfarin and in severe pain rated 9/10. IV access established.", patient_info:"78-year-old female, PMH: osteoporosis, atrial fibrillation, CHF. Takes warfarin, furosemide, digoxin.", vitals:{bp:"142/86",hr:"96 irregular",rr:"18",spo2:"96%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Classic hip fracture — right leg externally rotated and shortened. Pain 9/10. Distal CSM intact. Anticoagulated on warfarin. IV access established in left AC.", teaching_points:"1. AEMT scope includes IV fentanyl for pain management — adequate analgesia is both humane and reduces physiologic stress; start at 0.5 mcg/kg in elderly patients and titrate slowly. 2. Titrate carefully in elderly patients — reduced hepatic and renal clearance means standard doses can cause respiratory depression; reassess vitals and respiratory status after each dose." },
],

bd_bbq: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's BBQ Pit — male employee, partial thickness burns 18% BSA, IV fluids needed.", chief_complaint:"Partial thickness burns, 18% BSA, pain management", scene_description:"A male cook had boiling liquid knock over onto his right arm, chest and abdomen. Burns are blistering and severe. He is screaming in pain. The kitchen has been cleared by fire department.", patient_info:"34-year-old male, PMH: none, no medications.", vitals:{bp:"146/92",hr:"118",rr:"22",spo2:"97%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Partial thickness burns with blistering — approximately 18% BSA by Rule of Nines covering right arm and anterior trunk. No circumferential involvement. Airway patent. Pain rated 10/10. IV access established x2 large bore.", teaching_points:"1. AEMT scope includes IV fluid resuscitation for significant burns — establish large bore IV x2 and run NS for burns over 15% BSA; the Parkland formula guides 24-hour needs but in the field run fluids to maintain adequate perfusion. 2. IV fentanyl is appropriate and critical for large burns — under-treated burn pain causes massive sympathetic activation worsening hemodynamics; administer and titrate per protocol." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's BBQ Pit — male customer, AMS, blood glucose 28, diabetic emergency.", chief_complaint:"Severe hypoglycemia, GCS 7, cannot protect airway", scene_description:"A 52-year-old male is slumped in a corner booth, unresponsive to voice. He is a known diabetic wearing a medical alert bracelet. Diaphoretic and pale. Staff say he ate very little and was confused for 20 minutes before becoming unresponsive.", patient_info:"52-year-old male, PMH: Type 1 diabetes on insulin pump.", vitals:{bp:"108/68",hr:"108",rr:"14",spo2:"98%",gcs:"7",temp:"97.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"GCS 7 — cannot protect airway reliably. BG 28 mg/dL critically low. Cold and clammy. Insulin pump attached to abdomen. Cannot safely receive oral glucose at this GCS level.", teaching_points:"1. AEMT scope includes Dextrose 50% IV — for a patient who cannot protect their airway, D50 0.5g/kg IV is the appropriate treatment; establish IV and administer; expect improvement within 2-3 minutes if hypoglycemia is the primary cause. 2. If IV access cannot be established, glucagon 1mg IM is an AEMT intervention that stimulates hepatic glycogen release — it works slower than D50 but is effective without IV access." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's BBQ Pit — CO exposure, generator in back room, two patients.", chief_complaint:"Carbon monoxide poisoning, one confused, one unresponsive", scene_description:"Two employees were exposed to CO from a propane generator run indoors for 90 minutes. Patient 1 is confused with a severe headache. Patient 2 is unresponsive on the floor near the generator. Fire department has cleared the scene.", patient_info:"Patient 1: 41-year-old male. Patient 2: 52-year-old female. Both with unknown PMH.", vitals:{bp:"P1:138/84 P2:86/50",hr:"P1:104 P2:56",rr:"P1:22 P2:8",spo2:"P1:97% P2:84%",gcs:"P1:13 P2:5",temp:"P1:98.6°F P2:97.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"SpO2 unreliable in CO poisoning — reads falsely normal. Patient 2 in respiratory failure with GCS 5. Patient 1 symptomatic but stable. Both require 100% O2 via NRB immediately. IV access established on both.", teaching_points:"1. Standard pulse oximetry is unreliable in CO poisoning — it cannot differentiate COHgb from OxyHgb and gives falsely normal readings; treat based on clinical presentation and exposure history regardless of SpO2 reading. 2. Patient 2 needs BVM ventilation with 100% O2 and immediate transport — CO reduces the half-life of carboxyhemoglobin with 100% O2; transport to a facility with hyperbaric oxygen capability if available." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's BBQ Pit — 29-year-old female, post-ictal seizure, IV access needed.", chief_complaint:"Post-ictal seizure, known epileptic, missed medications", scene_description:"A female is post-ictal on the patio floor after a witnessed 3-minute generalized tonic-clonic seizure. She takes Keppra but missed her last two doses. She has a small abrasion on her cheek from falling. She is breathing on her own.", patient_info:"29-year-old female, PMH: epilepsy on levetiracetam. Missed 2 doses.", vitals:{bp:"132/78",hr:"106",rr:"14",spo2:"96%",gcs:"10",temp:"99.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Post-ictal with GCS 10. Airway maintained with recovery position. Respirations adequate. BG 92 mg/dL. Cheek abrasion minor. No other injuries noted. Missed Keppra doses likely precipitant.", teaching_points:"1. At the AEMT level, establish IV access in any post-ictal patient — if the patient seizes again en route you have immediate access for benzodiazepine administration; lorazepam or diazepam IV is appropriate for status epilepticus. 2. Always obtain a blood glucose in post-ictal patients — hypoglycemia can trigger or mimic seizures and is easily treated; this patient's BG of 92 rules it out but the habit must be automatic every time." },
],

bd_chinese: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Dragon Palace — 74-year-old male, acute stroke, FAST positive, LKW 25 minutes.", chief_complaint:"Acute ischemic stroke, FAST positive, in treatment window", scene_description:"An elderly male is seated at a back table with his wife. She noticed his face drooping mid-sentence during dinner. He has left facial droop, left arm drift, and slurred speech. Wife says it started about 25 minutes ago.", patient_info:"74-year-old male, PMH: hypertension, atrial fibrillation. Takes Eliquis and amlodipine.", vitals:{bp:"194/112",hr:"84 irregular",rr:"16",spo2:"96%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"FAST positive — left facial droop, left arm weak with drift, slurred dysarthric speech. LKW 25 minutes ago per wife. BG 108. On anticoagulation. Irregular rhythm consistent with known afib.", teaching_points:"1. At AEMT level your primary stroke intervention is time — establish IV access without delaying transport, perform a Cincinnati or LAMS stroke scale, and pre-notify the receiving stroke center with LKW time, deficits, and anticoagulant use. 2. Do NOT treat the hypertension in the field — elevated BP in acute stroke may be a compensatory mechanism to perfuse ischemic brain tissue; lowering it without imaging guidance can extend the infarct." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Dragon Palace — adult male choking, now unconscious, complete obstruction.", chief_complaint:"Complete airway obstruction, unconscious, cardiac arrest", scene_description:"A male who was choking on food at the buffet became unconscious after failed abdominal thrusts. He is now on the floor pulseless. Staff began CPR. You arrive to a full cardiac arrest with a known obstructed airway.", patient_info:"66-year-old male, PMH: dentures, hypertension.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"pulseless",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"Cardiac arrest secondary to airway obstruction. CPR in progress. BVM ventilation not moving chest — airway obstructed. Dentures visible in mouth — removed. Direct laryngoscopy may visualize the foreign body.", teaching_points:"1. At the AEMT level you can perform direct laryngoscopy to visualize and attempt removal of a foreign body with Magill forceps — this is the key intervention that differentiates your scope from BLS; visualize first, remove only if clearly visible. 2. If the airway cannot be cleared with laryngoscopy, continue CPR — chest compressions can generate enough airway pressure to expel a foreign body; do not stop compressions for prolonged airway attempts." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Dragon Palace — 81-year-old female, cardiac arrest, bystander CPR, V-fib.", chief_complaint:"V-fib cardiac arrest, witnessed collapse, AED on scene", scene_description:"An elderly female collapsed at her table. A nurse diner performed CPR. AED delivered one shock. Your unit arrives 5 minutes post-arrest. CPR ongoing. IV access established during CPR cycles. Monitor shows persistent V-fib.", patient_info:"81-year-old female, PMH: CHF, diabetes — per family.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"V-fib on monitor",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"Persistent V-fib after one AED shock. CPR ongoing with good quality compressions. IV access right AC established. Epinephrine 1mg IV administered. Family present and distressed.", teaching_points:"1. For V-fib arrest, defibrillation plus high-quality CPR is the algorithm — shock, resume CPR immediately for 2 minutes, reassess; at the AEMT level add epinephrine 1mg IV every 3-5 minutes to increase myocardial perfusion pressure. 2. Amiodarone 300mg IV is within AEMT scope for refractory V-fib persisting after 3 defibrillation attempts — it stabilizes the cardiac membrane and improves defibrillation success rate; know your protocol." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Dragon Palace — 70-year-old male, severe bronchospasm after eating shrimp.", chief_complaint:"Anaphylaxis with bronchospasm, possible COPD overlap", scene_description:"An elderly male is in tripod position at the buffet. He ate shrimp and developed progressive shortness of breath and wheezing over 10 minutes. He has a history of COPD and hives are developing on his forearms.", patient_info:"70-year-old male, PMH: COPD, hypertension, no known shellfish allergy.", vitals:{bp:"148/92",hr:"118",rr:"30",spo2:"88%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Bilateral expiratory wheeze. Hives developing on forearms. SpO2 88%. Using accessory muscles. Both allergic bronchospasm and COPD exacerbation possible. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Anaphylaxis with bronchospasm and urticaria is the primary diagnosis — epinephrine IM 0.3mg is first line even in a COPD patient; the risk of withholding epi in anaphylaxis outweighs the risk of giving it. 2. At the AEMT level you can administer nebulized albuterol for bronchospasm — this complements epinephrine and directly addresses the reactive airway component; set up the neb while packaging the patient." },
],

bd_pizza: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Pizza Palace — 17-year-old male, stab wound abdomen, hemorrhagic shock.", chief_complaint:"Penetrating abdominal trauma, hemorrhagic shock", scene_description:"Police on scene. A teenager was stabbed once in the left lower quadrant during a fight. He is pale and diaphoretic, tachycardic, and his BP is dropping. Two large bore IVs established.", patient_info:"17-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"88/60",hr:"138",rr:"26",spo2:"96%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Single stab wound LLQ approximately 2cm. Abdomen rigid and tender. Tachycardic and hypotensive — hemorrhagic shock. Skin pale, cool, diaphoretic. IV x2 large bore established.", teaching_points:"1. Hemorrhagic shock from penetrating abdominal trauma requires permissive hypotension in the field — target a systolic of 80-90 mmHg rather than running fluids wide open; excessive fluid resuscitation dilutes clotting factors and worsens outcomes. 2. Large bore IV access x2 is your priority — normal saline or LR bolus 250-500mL and reassess; do not delay transport for multiple IV attempts; IO is appropriate if IV access is unobtainable." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Pizza — 16-year-old female, status asthmaticus, silent chest.", chief_complaint:"Status asthmaticus, silent chest, pre-respiratory arrest", scene_description:"A teenage girl is outside the pizza shop in severe respiratory distress. She has used her albuterol inhaler eight times with no relief. She cannot speak in full sentences. Lips are slightly dusky. Auscultation reveals a silent chest.", patient_info:"16-year-old female, PMH: severe persistent asthma, uses albuterol and Flovent.", vitals:{bp:"126/80",hr:"128",rr:"36",spo2:"88%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Silent chest on auscultation — no wheeze audible, which is a critical sign indicating near-complete obstruction with no air movement. SpO2 88% despite apparent respiratory effort. Cyanosis at lips. Maximal accessory muscle use.", teaching_points:"1. A silent chest in asthma is a pre-arrest finding — the absence of wheeze does NOT mean improvement; it means there is so little air movement that turbulence cannot generate sound. Nebulized albuterol via AEMT scope is indicated immediately along with high-flow O2. 2. If SpO2 does not improve with neb treatment and the patient tires, prepare to assist ventilations with a BVM and request ALS intercept immediately." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Pizza — 8-year-old struck by vehicle, pediatric trauma, AMS developing.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric MVC trauma, altered mental status, shock", scene_description:"A child was struck by a slow-moving vehicle in the parking lot. He is on the ground and becoming increasingly lethargic. There is bruising developing across his abdomen from the bumper contact. He is confused about what happened.", patient_info:"8-year-old male, PMH: unknown, weight approximately 25kg.", vitals:{bp:"90/60",hr:"148",rr:"28",spo2:"95%",gcs:"12",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Tachycardic for age. Abdominal bruising across mid-abdomen — bumper sign. Altered mental status developing. Pediatric shock compensated — BP may appear acceptable while the child is in significant shock. Spinal precautions applied.", teaching_points:"1. Children compensate for shock longer than adults — a heart rate of 148 and altered mental status in an 8-year-old with abdominal trauma means significant blood loss is occurring even if the BP looks acceptable; treat aggressively and transport immediately. 2. If unable to establish IV within two attempts, IO access at the proximal tibia is appropriate in pediatric shock; do not delay fluid resuscitation for multiple failed IV attempts." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Pizza — 22-year-old male, deep laceration hand, arterial bleeding.", chief_complaint:"Arterial hand laceration, uncontrolled hemorrhage", scene_description:"A male employee cut his palm on an industrial pizza cutter. The towel is soaked through and pulsatile bright red bleeding is visible despite direct pressure. He is tachycardic and anxious. Cannot move index or middle finger.", patient_info:"22-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"106/68",hr:"122",rr:"20",spo2:"98%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Deep palmar laceration with pulsatile arterial bleeding not controlled by direct pressure alone. Two fingers with reduced sensation and movement. IV access established. Hemostatic dressing applied.", teaching_points:"1. Hemostatic dressings (QuikClot, Combat Gauze) are within AEMT scope for wounds where direct pressure alone is insufficient — pack the wound firmly, apply pressure for 3 minutes minimum, and reassess before transport. 2. Establish IV access and administer a fluid bolus if signs of early shock are present — tachycardia with a systolic of 106 in a young healthy male suggests 10-15% blood volume loss; normal saline 500mL bolus and reassess." },
],

bd_taco: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tacos — intoxicated male, unresponsive, vomitus in airway, respiratory depression.", chief_complaint:"Alcohol poisoning, airway compromise, hypoglycemia", scene_description:"A male is unresponsive on the sidewalk with vomitus visible around his mouth. He smells strongly of alcohol. He has a weak gag response and his respirations are 6 per minute and shallow.", patient_info:"Approximately 42-year-old male, PMH: unknown.", vitals:{bp:"96/56",hr:"54",rr:"6",spo2:"84%",gcs:"5",temp:"96.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Unresponsive with compromised airway from vomitus. SpO2 84%. Bradycardic. Hypothermic. BG 58 mg/dL — concurrent hypoglycemia. Gag reflex present but sluggish.", teaching_points:"1. Suction aggressively first, then position, then consider supraglottic airway if respirations remain inadequate — SpO2 of 84% with RR of 6 requires immediate airway intervention; an iGel or King LT is appropriate if BVM ventilation is inadequate. 2. Never assume altered mental status is purely alcohol — BG of 58 requires D50 IV; hypoglycemia compounding alcohol intoxication is dangerous and the correction is simple and fast." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tacos — 26-year-old female, 38 weeks pregnant, active labor, crowning present.", chief_complaint:"Imminent delivery, crowning, active labor", scene_description:"A 26-year-old female is contracting every 2 minutes leaning against the building. Her water broke 30 minutes ago. She has a strong urge to push. You inspect and find crowning is present — delivery is imminent.", patient_info:"26-year-old female, G2P1, 38 weeks, uncomplicated prenatal care.", vitals:{bp:"122/76",hr:"98",rr:"20",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Crowning present on inspection — delivery is imminent. Contractions every 2 minutes lasting 60 seconds. Membranes ruptured with clear fluid. No meconium. Previous vaginal delivery. OB kit opened and prepared.", teaching_points:"1. At the AEMT level manage the delivery — apply gentle counterpressure to the crowning head to prevent explosive delivery, guide the head out, check for nuchal cord, and deliver the shoulders with gentle downward then upward traction; do not pull. 2. After delivery, dry and stimulate the newborn, assess APGAR at 1 and 5 minutes, clamp and cut the cord, and keep the newborn warm — newborn thermoregulation is poor and a cold newborn is a sick newborn." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tacos — 23-year-old male, stimulant toxidrome, hyperthermia 103.2°F, agitated.", chief_complaint:"Stimulant OD, hyperthermia, extreme agitation", scene_description:"A young male is pacing erratically, soaked in sweat, and speaking to people who are not there. Bystanders say he ate something laced. He is combative when approached and his temperature is 103.2°F. Law enforcement is on scene.", patient_info:"23-year-old male, PMH: unknown. Suspected stimulant ingestion.", vitals:{bp:"172/108",hr:"142",rr:"26",spo2:"97%",gcs:"13",temp:"103.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Sympathomimetic toxidrome — hypertension, tachycardia, hyperthermia, dilated pupils, diaphoresis, agitation. Temperature 103.2°F. Risk of seizure and cardiac arrhythmia. IV access will require restraint assistance from law enforcement.", teaching_points:"1. Hyperthermia above 104°F in stimulant toxicity is the primary killer — active cooling (remove clothing, cool wet cloths, cool environment) should begin immediately; every degree above 104°F significantly increases the risk of rhabdomyolysis, seizure, and cardiac arrest. 2. At the AEMT level, benzodiazepines IV per protocol with medical direction can reduce agitation, lower BP and HR, and decrease seizure risk in stimulant toxicity." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tacos — 31-year-old female cyclist, TBI, GCS declining, herniation signs.", chief_complaint:"TBI, declining GCS, Cushing's triad developing", scene_description:"A female cyclist struck the back of her head on the pavement. She was briefly unconscious. GCS has declined from 14 to 11 in 8 minutes since EMS arrived. Her cracked helmet suggests significant impact force.", patient_info:"31-year-old female, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"148/72",hr:"58",rr:"10 irregular",spo2:"95%",gcs:"11 declining",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Declining GCS in 8 minutes. Bradycardia with widening pulse pressure — Cushing's triad developing. Irregular respirations. Right pupil 5mm, left 3mm — unequal pupils. Signs of impending herniation.", teaching_points:"1. Cushing's triad (hypertension, bradycardia, irregular respirations) with unequal pupils indicates impending herniation — keep head midline, elevate HOB 30 degrees if spinal injury is ruled out, and transport at maximum speed without delay for any other interventions. 2. Avoid hyperventilation — routine hyperventilation causes cerebral vasoconstriction and worsens ischemia; ventilate at a normal rate of 10-12 per minute unless herniation is confirmed, in which case mild hyperventilation to 20/min may be used as a bridge only." },
],

bd_diner: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's All-Night Diner — 61-year-old male trucker, inferior STEMI, RV involvement.", chief_complaint:"Inferior STEMI with right ventricular involvement", scene_description:"A large male trucker has been sitting in a corner booth for an hour looking pale. The overnight waitress called 911. He has jaw pain and left shoulder radiation. His 12-lead shows inferior STEMI with right-sided lead changes.", patient_info:"61-year-old male, PMH: hypertension uncontrolled, Type 2 diabetes, smoker x30 years.", vitals:{bp:"178/104",hr:"92",rr:"20",spo2:"94%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"12-lead shows ST elevation in II, III, aVF with reciprocal depression in I and aVL — inferior STEMI. Right-sided V4R also shows ST elevation suggesting RV involvement. Diaphoretic and pale. Lung sounds clear.", teaching_points:"1. RV infarction complicates inferior MI in approximately 40% of cases — RV infarction causes preload-dependent hemodynamics; nitrates and diuretics can cause catastrophic hypotension; IV fluid is the treatment for hypotension in RV MI. 2. Obtain a right-sided 12-lead (V4R) in any inferior STEMI before considering nitrates — ST elevation in V4R confirms RV involvement and changes your management significantly." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's All-Night Diner — 54-year-old female, critical hypoglycemia, GCS 6, insulin pump patient.", chief_complaint:"Critical hypoglycemia, BG 22, cannot protect airway", scene_description:"A female cook is found slumped at the break room table. She worked a double shift without eating. She is a Type 1 diabetic on an insulin pump. GCS 6 and she cannot protect her airway. BG reads 22 mg/dL.", patient_info:"54-year-old female, PMH: Type 1 DM on insulin pump.", vitals:{bp:"94/56",hr:"116",rr:"14",spo2:"97%",gcs:"6",temp:"97.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"BG 22 mg/dL critically low. GCS 6. Cannot protect airway reliably. Skin cold and clammy. Insulin pump on abdomen — consider pausing. IV access challenging but established.", teaching_points:"1. D50 0.5g/kg IV is your treatment — for a 70kg patient that is 25g of dextrose (50mL of D50); administer slowly over 3-5 minutes and recheck glucose within 5 minutes; if BG does not rise, repeat the dose. 2. If IV access cannot be obtained quickly, IO at the proximal tibia is appropriate in a critically hypoglycemic unresponsive patient — D50 can be administered IO; do not delay glucose correction struggling with IV access." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's All-Night Diner — 35-year-old male, excited delirium, hyperthermia, extreme agitation.", chief_complaint:"Excited delirium, temperature 105°F, cardiac arrest risk", scene_description:"A male has barricaded himself in a booth and is screaming incoherently. He has removed his clothing and is sweating profusely. Law enforcement is present. His estimated temperature is approximately 105°F based on skin presentation. Multiple officers needed to approach.", patient_info:"35-year-old male, PMH: schizophrenia, off medications x3 days per wife.", vitals:{bp:"unable",hr:"estimated 160+",rr:"rapid",spo2:"unable",gcs:"cannot assess",temp:"estimated 105°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Extreme agitation, hyperthermia, tachycardia, diaphoresis, and combativeness. Excited delirium presentation. Very high risk for sudden cardiac arrest. Will require chemical sedation for safe treatment.", teaching_points:"1. Excited delirium carries a significant risk of sudden cardiac arrest — the combination of hyperthermia, extreme catecholamine surge, and metabolic acidosis is lethal; your goals are sedation, cooling, and transport; do NOT use positional restraint (prone or hobble) as it increases arrest risk dramatically. 2. Chemical sedation with ketamine or benzodiazepines per medical direction is preferred over physical restraint alone — early sedation reduces mortality; communicate with medical direction early and document everything." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's All-Night Diner — 68-year-old female, thunderclap headache, BP 212/126.", chief_complaint:"Thunderclap headache, subarachnoid hemorrhage suspected", scene_description:"An elderly female was eating breakfast when she suddenly developed the worst headache of her life — she describes it as an explosion in her head with immediate onset. She has never had a headache like this before. Alert but in obvious pain and nauseated.", patient_info:"68-year-old female, PMH: hypertension on amlodipine.", vitals:{bp:"212/126",hr:"78",rr:"16",spo2:"98%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Sudden onset worst-ever headache. Neck stiffness noted. BP 212/126 — hypertensive emergency. No focal neuro deficits currently. Alert and oriented. Nausea present. Subarachnoid hemorrhage until proven otherwise.", teaching_points:"1. Sudden-onset worst headache of life is a subarachnoid hemorrhage until CT rules it out — do not administer anything that significantly alters blood pressure in the field; the elevated BP may be a Cushing response protecting the brain. 2. Transport priority is maximum — SAH has approximately 40% 30-day mortality; time to CT angiography and neurosurgical consultation is critical; pre-notify the receiving facility with suspected SAH to activate their neuro team." },
],

bd_coffee: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Brews — 21-year-old male, first seizure, post-ictal, IV access needed.", chief_complaint:"First-time seizure, post-ictal, unknown etiology", scene_description:"A college-age barista seized behind the counter for 90 seconds. He is post-ictal and confused. No prior seizure history. Blood glucose is normal. He has a tongue laceration from biting down during the event.", patient_info:"21-year-old male, PMH: none. No medications. Denies drug use.", vitals:{bp:"142/84",hr:"108",rr:"14",spo2:"97%",gcs:"11",temp:"98.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Post-ictal GCS 11. First ever seizure. BG 96 mg/dL. Tongue laceration with minor bleeding. No fever. No history of epilepsy, head injury, or drug use to explain the seizure. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. A first-time seizure in a young adult requires IV access and transport — the differential includes intracranial mass, electrolyte abnormality, cardiac arrhythmia, meningitis, and toxicology; none can be assessed in the field and all require hospital evaluation. 2. If the patient seizes again en route, lorazepam 0.1mg/kg IV or diazepam per protocol is your first-line treatment — be prepared to manage the airway aggressively after benzodiazepine administration as respiratory depression is a significant side effect." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Brews — 24-year-old female, anaphylaxis, bee sting, stridor, epi needed.", chief_complaint:"Anaphylaxis, stridor, distributive shock", scene_description:"A barista was stung on the neck while working outside. She developed generalized hives, facial swelling, and stridor within 5 minutes. Her EpiPen is in her car. She is now in obvious distress with worsening stridor and a BP of 86/50.", patient_info:"24-year-old female, PMH: known bee allergy with prior mild reaction.", vitals:{bp:"86/50",hr:"132",rr:"28",spo2:"91%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Stridor audible without stethoscope. Angioedema of lips and tongue. Widespread urticaria. Hypotensive. Stinger still visible in neck. SpO2 91% and declining. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Epinephrine 1:1000 0.3mg IM to the lateral thigh immediately — establish IV access simultaneously but do not delay epi when the airway is closing; it is the only intervention that reverses both the airway compromise and the cardiovascular collapse. 2. After epinephrine, establish large bore IV and begin normal saline bolus — anaphylactic shock involves massive third spacing and capillary leak; fluid resuscitation is the second pillar of treatment after epinephrine." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Brews — 56-year-old male, syncope from barstool, bradycardia 46, hypotension.", chief_complaint:"Syncope, symptomatic bradycardia, head injury", scene_description:"A male fainted from a barstool and struck the back of his head on the counter. He is alert but bradycardic at 46 bpm and hypotensive. He is on metoprolol and did not eat today. He has an occipital hematoma.", patient_info:"56-year-old male, PMH: hypertension on metoprolol. History of prior syncope.", vitals:{bp:"82/50",hr:"46",rr:"16",spo2:"98%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Symptomatic bradycardia at 46 bpm with hypotension. On beta blocker. Occipital hematoma from counter strike. Monitor shows sinus bradycardia, no heart block. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Symptomatic bradycardia (HR less than 60 with hypotension) is treated with atropine 0.5mg IV at the AEMT level — repeat every 3-5 minutes to a max of 3mg; beta blocker effect can cause refractory bradycardia that may not respond well to atropine. 2. The head strike complicates management — obtain a thorough neuro exam and treat the bradycardia simultaneously; a patient who fainted and hit their head needs both cardiac monitoring and head CT imaging at the hospital." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Brews — 3-year-old, caffeine toxicity, HR 172, tremors, vomiting.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric caffeine ingestion, tachycardia, tremors", scene_description:"A toddler grabbed a bag of espresso beans from a display and ate approximately 30 beans. He is trembling, vomiting, and his heart rate is 172. His mother is frantic. The child is alert but clearly distressed and uncomfortable.", patient_info:"3-year-old male, PMH: none. Weight approximately 14 kg.", vitals:{bp:"118/74",hr:"172",rr:"30",spo2:"98%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Tachycardic, tremulous, vomiting. Pupils dilated. Alert but clearly uncomfortable. Monitor shows sinus tachycardia. Caffeine toxicity can cause seizures and cardiac arrhythmias in small children. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Caffeine toxicity in small children is serious — seizures, dysrhythmias, and hemodynamic instability can occur; establish IV access, place on cardiac monitor, and transport; bring the product packaging for poison control. 2. Call Poison Control (1-800-222-1222) en route — for pediatric ingestions Poison Control guides the receiving ER on observation time, treatment thresholds, and specific management; they should be part of every significant pediatric ingestion call." },
],

bd_grocery: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Food King — male, 63-year-old, cardiac arrest, V-fib, AED on wall.", chief_complaint:"V-fib cardiac arrest, bystander CPR, AED available", scene_description:"A heavyset male collapsed in the produce section. Bystander CPR in progress. AED is on the wall near customer service. Your unit arrives 6 minutes after the call. Monitor confirms V-fib. IV access established during CPR.", patient_info:"63-year-old male, PMH: unknown per wife.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"V-fib on monitor",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"V-fib on monitor confirmed. Bystander CPR in progress with good compression quality. One AED shock delivered before arrival. IV access established right AC. Epinephrine 1mg IV administered.", teaching_points:"1. For V-fib arrest, defibrillation plus high-quality CPR is the algorithm — shock, resume CPR immediately for 2 minutes, reassess; at the AEMT level add epinephrine 1mg IV every 3-5 minutes to increase coronary perfusion pressure. 2. Amiodarone 300mg IV is within AEMT scope for refractory V-fib after 3 defibrillation attempts and epinephrine — it stabilizes the cardiac membrane and improves defibrillation success rate." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Food King — 72-year-old female, Colles fracture, warfarin patient, IV analgesia.", chief_complaint:"Distal radius fracture, severe pain, anticoagulated", scene_description:"An elderly female fell from a step stool in aisle 7 and landed on her outstretched right hand. Her wrist is visibly deformed. She is on warfarin for atrial fibrillation. She is alert and in moderate to severe pain.", patient_info:"72-year-old female, PMH: osteoporosis, afib. Takes warfarin and calcium.", vitals:{bp:"148/88",hr:"92",rr:"16",spo2:"98%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Obvious distal forearm deformity — Colles fracture. Distal CSM intact. On warfarin — bleeding risk elevated. Pain 7/10. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. AEMT scope includes IV fentanyl — 0.5 mcg/kg IV in this elderly patient and titrate to effect; adequate pain control reduces patient movement that could further displace the fracture and improves overall outcome. 2. Document warfarin use and communicate to the ER — warfarin elevates the risk of hematoma formation at the fracture site; the ER needs to know to check INR and potentially reverse anticoagulation before any surgical fixation." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Food King — 4-year-old, opioid ingestion from mother's purse, respiratory failure.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric opioid ingestion, critical respiratory depression", scene_description:"A 4-year-old accessed his mother's purse near the pharmacy counter and ingested oxycodone. He is barely responsive with pinpoint pupils and respiratory depression. SpO2 80%. Mother is frantic. IO access established.", patient_info:"4-year-old male, PMH: none. Weight approximately 16 kg.", vitals:{bp:"76/44",hr:"46",rr:"6",spo2:"80%",gcs:"5",temp:"96.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Pediatric opioid toxidrome — miosis, respiratory depression, decreased LOC. SpO2 80%. HR 46. BVM ventilation improving SpO2. IO access established at proximal tibia. Naloxone drawn up.", teaching_points:"1. Pediatric naloxone dosing is weight-based — 0.01mg/kg IV/IO/IN; for this 16kg child that is 0.16mg; titrate to restore adequate respirations not to full reversal, as abrupt reversal causes acute withdrawal and pulmonary edema. 2. IO access at the proximal tibia is appropriate when IV cannot be rapidly established in a critically ill child — IO access gets your drugs on board within 30 seconds of placement; do not delay for multiple failed IV attempts." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Food King — 31-year-old female, anaphylaxis, deli counter, tree nut exposure.", chief_complaint:"Anaphylaxis, stridor, distributive shock, SpO2 88%", scene_description:"A female sampled a deli product containing tree nuts — a known allergen. She developed urticaria, facial swelling, and is now in severe respiratory distress with stridor. Her EpiPen is in the car. BP is critically low.", patient_info:"31-year-old female, PMH: tree nut allergy. Usually carries EpiPen.", vitals:{bp:"78/44",hr:"138",rr:"32",spo2:"88%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Anaphylactic shock with airway compromise. Stridor audible. SpO2 88% declining. GCS 14 and declining from cerebral hypoperfusion. Widespread urticaria. IV access established large bore.", teaching_points:"1. This is the most severe anaphylaxis presentation — airway compromise PLUS shock; epinephrine IM immediately followed by IV fluid bolus; if stridor worsens after epi consider supraglottic airway before complete closure occurs. 2. Second epinephrine dose 0.3mg IM is appropriate if there is no improvement in 5-15 minutes — anaphylaxis refractory to one dose requires repeat dosing and early ALS intercept for possible epinephrine infusion." },
],

bd_dollar: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Dollar Deals — male, stabbed in chest, tension pneumothorax developing.", chief_complaint:"Penetrating chest trauma, tension pneumothorax", scene_description:"Police on scene after a robbery. A male employee was stabbed in the right chest. He initially had decreased breath sounds on the right. Over 3 minutes he has deteriorated dramatically — now hypotensive with trachea deviating left.", patient_info:"28-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"72/40",hr:"138",rr:"32",spo2:"82%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Classic tension pneumothorax — tracheal deviation LEFT away from tension side, absent breath sounds RIGHT, JVD developing, hypotension, declining SpO2. This is a clinical diagnosis — do not wait for imaging.", teaching_points:"1. Tension pneumothorax is a clinical diagnosis requiring immediate needle decompression — at the AEMT level perform needle decompression at the 2nd intercostal space midclavicular line on the affected side; a rush of air confirms the diagnosis and the patient should improve immediately. 2. After needle decompression apply a vented chest seal to the original wound if not already done — this prevents re-accumulation of the tension pneumothorax and maintains the decompression you just achieved." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Dollar Deals — 80-year-old male, anticoagulated, head trauma, declining GCS.", chief_complaint:"Head trauma, anticoagulated, GCS declining from 14 to 11", scene_description:"An elderly male with dementia tripped on a floor mat and struck his forehead on a display shelf. He has a 3cm forehead laceration. His GCS has dropped from 14 to 11 in 10 minutes since the fall. He is on Xarelto.", patient_info:"80-year-old male, PMH: dementia, hypertension, afib. Takes Xarelto.", vitals:{bp:"162/94",hr:"80 irregular",rr:"16",spo2:"96%",gcs:"11 declining",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Declining GCS in an anticoagulated elderly patient with head trauma — intracranial hemorrhage likely and expanding. Forehead laceration controlled. Right pupil slightly larger than left. Afib rhythm on monitor.", teaching_points:"1. A declining GCS after head trauma in an anticoagulated patient is an emergency within an emergency — intracranial bleeding is likely expanding rapidly due to Xarelto; communicate the anticoagulant name and last dose to the ER immediately as reversal agents must be activated quickly. 2. Establish IV access and transport immediately — do not delay for splinting or wound management; the expanding intracranial bleed is the immediate threat to life." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Dollar Deals — 43-year-old female, heat stroke, temp 104.8°F, hot dry skin.", chief_complaint:"Heat stroke, anhidrosis, altered mental status", scene_description:"A female was found collapsed in the hot parking lot. Her skin is HOT and DRY. She is confused and cannot tell you her name. Temperature is 104.8°F. Outside temp is 97°F and she had been shopping for over two hours.", patient_info:"43-year-old female, PMH: hypertension on hydrochlorothiazide.", vitals:{bp:"88/52",hr:"128",rr:"24",spo2:"97%",gcs:"11",temp:"104.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Heat stroke — hot DRY skin, temperature 104.8°F, altered mental status. Diuretic use worsened dehydration. No sweating — anhidrosis indicates failure of thermoregulatory system. Large bore IV x2 established.", teaching_points:"1. Heat stroke with anhidrosis and altered mental status requires aggressive cooling — ice packs to axilla, groin, and neck, wet sheets with fanning, cool IV fluids; every minute above 104°F increases the risk of rhabdomyolysis, seizure, DIC, and multiorgan failure. 2. IV fluid resuscitation with cold normal saline serves two purposes — volume replacement for dehydration AND active internal cooling; run 1-2 liters rapidly while continuing external cooling measures simultaneously." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Dollar Deals — 2-year-old, found in hot car, critical hyperthermia, temp 106°F.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric heat stroke, temp 106°F, GCS 6, critical", scene_description:"A bystander broke a car window after seeing a toddler alone in the lot. Outside is 94°F. The child is limp and minimally responsive with hot dry skin. Temperature is 106.2°F. Estimated time in car is 90 minutes.", patient_info:"Approximately 2-year-old female, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"70/38",hr:"172",rr:"38 shallow",spo2:"92%",gcs:"6",temp:"106.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Critical pediatric heat stroke. Temperature 106.2°F. GCS 6. Tachycardic with weak pulses. Shock physiology. Hot dry skin. Seizure risk imminent at this temperature. IO access established.", teaching_points:"1. Pediatric heat stroke above 106°F is immediately life threatening — aggressive cooling AND hemodynamic resuscitation are simultaneous priorities; cold NS 20mL/kg IO bolus, ice packs to axilla and groin, strip all clothing. 2. Anticipate seizure — a child with a temperature of 106°F is at very high risk; have your airway equipment ready and benzodiazepine drawn up; cooling is the primary seizure prevention in this patient." },
],

bd_pharmacy: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Rx Pharmacy — 79-year-old male, digoxin and metoprolol OD, HR 38.", chief_complaint:"Beta blocker and digoxin OD, complete heart block", scene_description:"A 79-year-old male was found confused in the pharmacy waiting area with empty blister packs of metoprolol and digoxin nearby. He is barely responsive. Heart rate is 38 bpm and blood pressure is critically low.", patient_info:"79-year-old male, PMH: CHF, hypertension, afib, depression. Takes metoprolol, digoxin, lisinopril.", vitals:{bp:"76/44",hr:"38",rr:"10",spo2:"92%",gcs:"8",temp:"97.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Severe symptomatic bradycardia from beta blocker and digoxin overdose. GCS 8. SpO2 92%. Monitor shows complete heart block with ventricular escape rhythm at 38 bpm. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Beta blocker and digoxin overdose causing complete heart block is often refractory to atropine — atropine works on vagal tone but complete heart block may bypass this mechanism; transcutaneous pacing is within AEMT scope and may be required to maintain perfusion en route. 2. Calcium chloride is sometimes used for beta blocker OD to overcome calcium channel inhibition — check your specific AEMT protocol and medical direction; digoxin toxicity management differs and calcium is relatively contraindicated in digoxin toxicity." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Rx Pharmacy — 82-year-old female, post-vaccine anaphylaxis, refractory to first epi.", chief_complaint:"Biphasic anaphylaxis, refractory to first epinephrine dose", scene_description:"An 82-year-old female received a flu vaccine and developed anaphylaxis. The pharmacist administered epinephrine 0.3mg IM 8 minutes ago. She initially improved slightly but is worsening again — stridor is returning and BP remains critically low.", patient_info:"82-year-old female, PMH: CHF, hypertension, afib. Takes furosemide, digoxin, metoprolol.", vitals:{bp:"72/42",hr:"128 irregular",rr:"30",spo2:"86%",gcs:"11",temp:"98.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Biphasic anaphylaxis reaction — initial epi effect wearing off with return of anaphylactic shock. GCS 11. SpO2 86%. Stridor audible. Afib with RVR on monitor. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Biphasic anaphylaxis occurs in up to 20% of cases — a second dose of epinephrine 0.3mg IM is indicated when the first dose's effect wanes; do not hesitate to give it when symptoms are returning. 2. This patient's cardiac comorbidities make epinephrine riskier but the risk of anaphylaxis killing her outweighs the risk of epinephrine-induced arrhythmia; give the epi, establish IV for fluid support, and transport rapidly." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Rx Pharmacy — 33-year-old female, status epilepticus, 7 minutes ongoing.", chief_complaint:"Status epilepticus, active seizure 7 minutes, airway at risk", scene_description:"A 33-year-old female has been actively seizing in the pharmacy for 7 minutes. The seizure has not stopped. No history known. She is still in full tonic-clonic activity. Her airway is at immediate risk and hypoxia is developing.", patient_info:"33-year-old female, PMH: unknown, no medical alert jewelry.", vitals:{bp:"unable",hr:"unable",rr:"irregular during seizure",spo2:"unable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"Active generalized tonic-clonic seizure now 7 minutes in duration — status epilepticus. Airway at immediate risk. Hypoxia developing. IO access being established given IV difficulty during active seizure.", teaching_points:"1. Status epilepticus is a neurological emergency — benzodiazepine administration is the treatment; at the AEMT level lorazepam 0.1mg/kg IV/IO or diazepam 5-10mg IV/IO per protocol; IN midazolam is an alternative if vascular access is unavailable. 2. IO access is appropriate when IV cannot be rapidly established in a seizing patient — the tibial IO provides fast reliable access for benzodiazepine delivery without requiring vein identification during convulsions." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Rx Pharmacy — 71-year-old male, nitrate/Viagra interaction, BP 68/40.", chief_complaint:"Nitrate and PDE5 inhibitor interaction, severe hypotension", scene_description:"A 71-year-old male took his new nitroglycerin prescription for chest pain before entering the pharmacy. He is now on the floor of the parking lot barely conscious. He admits to taking sildenafil yesterday. BP is 68/40.", patient_info:"71-year-old male, PMH: CAD, prior MI. Takes aspirin, sildenafil as needed, just prescribed nitroglycerin.", vitals:{bp:"68/40",hr:"112",rr:"18",spo2:"96%",gcs:"11",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Severe hypotension from nitrate/PDE5 inhibitor interaction. GCS 11 and declining. Chest pain still present at 4/10. Monitor shows sinus tachycardia, no ST elevation. Large bore IV x2 established.", teaching_points:"1. Nitrates are absolutely contraindicated within 24-48 hours of PDE5 inhibitor use — the combination causes profound refractory hypotension; treatment is IV fluid resuscitation targeting systolic above 90 mmHg and supportive care. 2. Always ask about erectile dysfunction medication use before administering or approving nitroglycerin — this interaction is both common and potentially fatal; it must be part of your medication history every single time." },
],

bd_cbd: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's CBD and Wellness — 29-year-old male, kratom OD, respiratory failure, on Suboxone.", chief_complaint:"Kratom and opioid interaction, respiratory failure", scene_description:"A young male purchased high-dose kratom extract and consumed it in the store. He is now unresponsive with near-agonal respirations. He is also on buprenorphine (Suboxone). The combination has caused severe respiratory depression.", patient_info:"29-year-old male, PMH: opioid use disorder on suboxone 8mg/2mg daily.", vitals:{bp:"88/52",hr:"50",rr:"4",spo2:"74%",gcs:"4",temp:"97.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Respiratory failure. SpO2 74%. Bradycardic at 50. GCS 4. Pinpoint pupils. BVM ventilation needed immediately. On Suboxone — buprenorphine occupies mu receptors and competes with naloxone making response less predictable.", teaching_points:"1. Kratom has opioid agonist activity — treat as opioid OD; however in a Suboxone patient, naloxone response may be partial or delayed because buprenorphine has high receptor affinity; the primary intervention is BVM ventilation and airway management. 2. Supraglottic airway placement is within AEMT scope for an apneic patient — if BVM ventilation is inadequate, place an iGel or King LT immediately; do not continue ineffective BVM ventilation when a better airway option is available." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's CBD and Wellness — 16-year-old female, high-dose CBD and SSRI, serotonin syndrome.", chief_complaint:"Serotonin syndrome, agitation, tremors, hyperthermia", scene_description:"A 16-year-old female ingested approximately 1000mg of CBD gummies. She takes escitalopram. She is now tremulous, agitated, diaphoretic, and has muscle rigidity. Her temperature is elevated at 102.6°F.", patient_info:"16-year-old female, PMH: anxiety. Takes escitalopram 10mg daily.", vitals:{bp:"138/88",hr:"128",rr:"22",spo2:"98%",gcs:"13",temp:"102.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Agitation, tremors, diaphoresis, muscle rigidity, and hyperthermia — serotonin syndrome triad (neuromuscular abnormality, autonomic instability, altered mental status). CBD can inhibit CYP enzymes increasing escitalopram levels. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Serotonin syndrome presents with the triad of altered mental status, autonomic instability (tachycardia, hyperthermia, diaphoresis), and neuromuscular findings (tremor, rigidity, clonus) — it can be life threatening and progresses rapidly; cooling, benzodiazepines for agitation, and rapid transport are your interventions. 2. At the AEMT level benzodiazepines IV are first-line for serotonin syndrome agitation and rigidity — they reduce muscle activity, lower temperature, and decrease catecholamine surge; administer per protocol with medical direction." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's CBD and Wellness — 23-year-old female, syncope, 8 weeks pregnant, hypotensive.", chief_complaint:"Syncope, first trimester pregnancy, ectopic cannot be excluded", scene_description:"A 23-year-old female store clerk fainted and struck her chin on the display counter. She is now alert but hypotensive and tachycardic. She discloses she is 8 weeks pregnant and has had morning sickness preventing her from keeping food down.", patient_info:"23-year-old female, PMH: none. 8 weeks pregnant, G1P0.", vitals:{bp:"84/50",hr:"106",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Hypotensive and tachycardic in first trimester pregnancy. Ectopic pregnancy cannot be ruled out — location not confirmed. Chin laceration controlled. Dehydrated from hyperemesis. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. In first trimester pregnancy with hypotension and tachycardia you cannot rule out ectopic pregnancy without imaging — even though the patient attributes symptoms to dehydration, ruptured ectopic presents exactly this way; establish IV and administer NS bolus while transporting urgently to an OB-capable facility. 2. IV fluid resuscitation is appropriate for hyperemesis-related dehydration in pregnancy — normal saline 500mL bolus is safe and will help distinguish simple dehydration from hemorrhagic etiology by whether the patient responds to fluids." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's CBD and Wellness — 61-year-old male, 12-lead ST depression, presents as panic attack.", chief_complaint:"Lateral ST depression on 12-lead, diaphoresis, high-risk demographics", scene_description:"A 61-year-old male with anxiety history developed chest tightness in the store. He has had panic attacks before. However he is diaphoretic — atypical for his usual anxiety episodes. 12-lead acquired shows ST depression.", patient_info:"61-year-old male, PMH: GAD, hypertension. Father died of MI at 62. Takes sertraline and amlodipine.", vitals:{bp:"166/102",hr:"122",rr:"28",spo2:"97%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"12-lead shows ST depression in V4-V6 and aVL — concerning for lateral wall ischemia or NSTEMI. Diaphoresis present. Strong family history of early cardiac death. Tachycardic and anxious.", teaching_points:"1. ST depression in lateral leads combined with diaphoresis in a 61-year-old male with cardiac family history is ACS until proven otherwise — aspirin, IV access, O2 if needed, and transport to a cardiac center regardless of how much it resembles anxiety. 2. The 12-lead acquired in the field is a critical tool — document the changes precisely, transmit or bring a copy to the ER, and communicate your findings on the radio report so the team is prepared." },
],

bd_smoke: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Smoke Shack — 67-year-old male, severe COPD exacerbation, SpO2 80%, CPAP candidate.", chief_complaint:"COPD exacerbation, SpO2 80%, pre-respiratory failure", scene_description:"A regular customer with severe COPD is outside in severe distress. He is in tripod position, using all accessory muscles, and can speak only 1-2 words at a time. SpO2 is 80% on room air. He is still holding a cigarette when you arrive.", patient_info:"67-year-old male, PMH: severe COPD, CHF, hypertension. Continues to smoke.", vitals:{bp:"158/96",hr:"118",rr:"36",spo2:"80%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"SpO2 80% — critical hypoxia. Severe respiratory distress with tripod positioning. Distant breath sounds with expiratory wheeze. Barrel chest. Pursed lip breathing. Peak flow markedly reduced.", teaching_points:"1. CPAP at 5-10 cmH2O is the priority AEMT intervention for severe COPD exacerbation — it reduces the work of breathing, improves oxygenation, and prevents respiratory failure; apply immediately with supplemental O2 titrated to maintain SpO2 88-92%. 2. Nebulized albuterol and ipratropium should be administered simultaneously through the CPAP circuit if available — bronchodilation combined with CPAP addresses both the mechanical obstruction and the work of breathing." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Smoke Shack — 17-year-old male, EVALI, SpO2 88%, bilateral crackles.", chief_complaint:"EVALI — vaping associated lung injury, severe hypoxia", scene_description:"A 17-year-old heavy vaper is brought in by his father after a week of worsening dyspnea and fever. He can barely walk from the car. SpO2 is 88% on room air and he has bilateral coarse crackles throughout both lung fields.", patient_info:"17-year-old male, PMH: none. Heavy THC and nicotine vaping x6 months.", vitals:{bp:"118/74",hr:"114",rr:"30",spo2:"88%",gcs:"15",temp:"101.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Bilateral crackles — EVALI causes diffuse alveolar damage similar to ARDS. SpO2 88% on room air. Tachycardic and tachypneic. No wheeze. Improving to 93% with 4L nasal cannula. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. EVALI causes diffuse alveolar damage — supplemental O2 is the primary field treatment; CPAP may be beneficial if SpO2 does not improve with simple O2 supplementation; rapid transport to a hospital capable of CT imaging and potential ICU admission is essential. 2. Always ask about vaping history in young patients with respiratory complaints — EVALI can present similarly to pneumonia or pulmonary edema and is frequently missed without a thorough history." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Smoke Shack — 44-year-old female, occipital head injury, neck pain, spinal precautions.", chief_complaint:"Head and neck injury from fall, midline cervical tenderness", scene_description:"A female slipped on a wet spot in the parking lot and struck the back of her head on the curb. She has an occipital laceration and severe neck pain. She was briefly confused after the fall and cannot recall the impact.", patient_info:"44-year-old female, PMH: migraines, takes sumatriptan.", vitals:{bp:"138/84",hr:"90",rr:"16",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Occipital laceration 2cm with controlled bleeding. Midline neck pain with palpation at C4-C5 level. Post-traumatic amnesia — cannot recall the fall. Neuro exam intact but cervical midline tenderness requires spinal immobilization.", teaching_points:"1. Midline cervical tenderness in a trauma patient with mechanism for spinal injury requires spinal immobilization — apply a cervical collar and use a long board or scoop stretcher; document neuro exam before and after immobilization. 2. Cervical collar sizing matters — an improperly sized collar can worsen a spinal injury; measure neck height from shoulder to jaw and select the appropriate size; if uncertain between sizes, choose the smaller one and supplement with manual stabilization." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Smoke Shack — 58-year-old male, anterior STEMI, 3 weeks post-stent, still smoking.", chief_complaint:"In-stent thrombosis, anterior STEMI, 12-lead changes", scene_description:"A 58-year-old male with a coronary stent placed 3 weeks ago is behind the counter with chest pain identical to his prior MI. He is still smoking. His 12-lead shows new ST elevation in V2-V4.", patient_info:"58-year-old male, PMH: MI 3 weeks ago, coronary stent. Takes aspirin, Plavix, metoprolol, atorvastatin.", vitals:{bp:"152/92",hr:"96",rr:"20",spo2:"94%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"ST elevation in V2-V4 — anterior STEMI pattern. New changes from his prior 12-lead. Diaphoretic and pale. On dual antiplatelet therapy post-stent. SpO2 94% on room air.", teaching_points:"1. In-stent thrombosis presents as STEMI and is a catheterization emergency — activate the cath lab via your 12-lead transmission or radio report immediately; time to re-opening is critical and every minute of delay increases permanent myocardial damage. 2. This patient is already on aspirin and Plavix — do not give additional aspirin if the full dose was already taken today; oxygen via nasal cannula to maintain SpO2 above 94% and rapid transport to a PCI-capable center are your priorities." },
],

bd_carwash: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Car Wash — male, arm trapped in conveyor, crush injury, open fracture, shock.", chief_complaint:"Crush injury, open fracture, hemorrhagic shock", scene_description:"Fire department has freed the patient's arm from the conveyor belt. The right forearm has a severe crush injury with bone visible through the wound and massive soft tissue damage. He is in shock. Two large bore IVs established.", patient_info:"31-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"84/50",hr:"148",rr:"28",spo2:"96%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Open fracture with bone visible. Hemorrhagic shock — BP 84/50, HR 148. Crush mechanism with approximately 12 minutes of entrapment. Two large bore IVs established. Tourniquet considered for arterial hemorrhage.", teaching_points:"1. Reperfusion injury after crush syndrome can cause fatal cardiac arrhythmias due to sudden release of potassium, myoglobin, and lactic acid — IV fluid resuscitation with normal saline before and after extrication helps dilute these byproducts; communicate crush mechanism and duration to the ER. 2. Monitor closely for compartment syndrome — crush injuries can develop compartment syndrome in adjacent compartments even without direct injury; document every CSM assessment with a timestamp." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Car Wash — 74-year-old male, unresponsive in vehicle, hypoglycemia plus CO exposure.", chief_complaint:"Dual etiology — critical hypoglycemia and CO exposure", scene_description:"An elderly male was found slumped over his steering wheel inside the enclosed wash tunnel with the engine running. SpO2 reads 97% but is unreliable. His glucometer reads 28 mg/dL. He has a pulse but is unresponsive.", patient_info:"74-year-old male, PMH: Type 2 diabetes, insulin-dependent.", vitals:{bp:"138/84",hr:"74",rr:"12",spo2:"97% unreliable",gcs:"6",temp:"97.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"GCS 6. BG 28 mg/dL critically low. Possible concurrent CO exposure — SpO2 unreliable. Breathing adequately. IV access established. Patient removed from CO source immediately.", teaching_points:"1. Multiple concurrent problems require simultaneous treatment — remove from CO source, apply 15 LPM O2 via NRB, AND administer D50 for hypoglycemia; do not focus on one diagnosis and miss the other. 2. When a patient has two potential causes for altered mental status treat both — D50 for hypoglycemia is fast, safe, and diagnostic; if the patient improves dramatically after D50, hypoglycemia was primary, but CO exposure still requires 100% O2 and hospital evaluation." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Car Wash — 38-year-old female, ankle fracture, IV pain management, morphine allergy.", chief_complaint:"Ankle fracture, fentanyl needed, morphine allergic patient", scene_description:"A female slipped on wet concrete near the vacuum stations. Her left ankle is visibly deformed with immediate swelling. She is in significant pain and reports a morphine allergy causing nausea and vomiting. IV access established.", patient_info:"38-year-old female, PMH: morphine allergy (GI side effects). No other PMH.", vitals:{bp:"132/80",hr:"98",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Left ankle deformity with swelling and ecchymosis. Pain 7/10. Distal CSM intact. Morphine allergy — fentanyl is the appropriate alternative. No head or spinal involvement. IV access established in right AC.", teaching_points:"1. Fentanyl is the preferred analgesic when morphine allergy is reported — it is a synthetic opioid with no cross-reactivity to morphine in most cases; administer 1 mcg/kg IV slowly and titrate to effect, reassessing pain and vitals after each dose. 2. Drug allergy documentation matters — always document the specific reaction when a patient reports an allergy; a GI side effect is different from anaphylaxis and changes which alternative you select; true opioid allergy is rare but fentanyl is the safest choice." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Car Wash — 27-year-old male, bilateral chemical eye injury, alkaline degreaser pH 12.5.", chief_complaint:"Bilateral alkaline eye injury, continuous irrigation needed", scene_description:"A male employee was sprayed with an alkaline degreaser in both eyes. He has been rinsing at the sink for 5 minutes. Both eyes are bright red with excessive tearing and he cannot keep them open. The MSDS sheet confirms pH 12.5.", patient_info:"27-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"134/82",hr:"106",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Bilateral conjunctival injection and chemosis. Cannot open eyes due to pain. Alkaline chemical continues to penetrate tissue even after rinsing. MSDS confirms pH 12.5. Morgan lenses or continuous IV tubing irrigation required.", teaching_points:"1. Alkaline eye injuries are more serious than acid burns because they continue to saponify ocular tissue even after the chemical is removed — continuous copious irrigation must continue throughout transport; Morgan lenses connected to IV saline tubing provide hands-free continuous irrigation. 2. The goal of irrigation is to get the ocular pH between 7.0-7.4 — if you have pH paper, check the ocular pH every 5 minutes and continue irrigation until neutral; do not stop based on patient comfort alone." },
],

bd_laundry: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Laundromat — 24-year-old female, DV assault, 28 weeks pregnant, abdominal trauma.", chief_complaint:"Domestic violence, pregnant, uterine tenderness, abruption risk", scene_description:"A 24-year-old female at 28 weeks gestation was assaulted by her partner. She has periorbital hematoma and rib tenderness. She is reporting increasing lower abdominal cramping since being pushed against a wall. Uterus is firm and tender between contractions.", patient_info:"24-year-old female, G2P1, 28 weeks pregnant. No PMH.", vitals:{bp:"118/76",hr:"112",rr:"22",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Tachycardic. Uterus firm and tender between contractions — abruption sign. Lower abdominal pain increasing. Fetal movement reported by patient. Facial trauma. IV x2 large bore established.", teaching_points:"1. Uterine tenderness and rigidity between contractions after trauma suggest placental abruption — this can cause fetal death and maternal hemorrhage rapidly; IV x2 large bore, left lateral position, and transport to an OB-capable trauma center are your priorities. 2. Fetal heart tones are difficult to assess in the field — their presence is reassuring but their absence does not confirm fetal demise; your priority is maternal stabilization as that provides the best fetal outcome." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Laundromat — 3-year-old, caustic ingestion, laundry detergent, stridor developing.", chief_complaint:"Caustic ingestion, chemical burns, stridor, airway at risk", scene_description:"A 3-year-old found an unlocked supply closet and ingested concentrated laundry detergent. He has chemical burns visible around his lips and is drooling excessively. Stridor is developing as the caustic chemical burns his upper airway.", patient_info:"3-year-old male, PMH: none. Weight approximately 15 kg.", vitals:{bp:"78/44",hr:"152",rr:"34 with stridor",spo2:"91%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Stridor developing — upper airway chemical burn from caustic ingestion. Chemical burns on lips and chin. Excessive drooling. SpO2 91% and declining. Airway is at imminent risk of swelling shut from progressive burns.", teaching_points:"1. Caustic airway burns can progress to complete obstruction rapidly — high-flow O2, position of comfort, and immediate transport with continuous airway monitoring; do NOT induce vomiting and do NOT attempt to neutralize the chemical in the field. 2. At the AEMT level if stridor worsens and SpO2 declines despite O2, consider a nasopharyngeal airway as a temporizing measure — an NPA maintains the upper airway and may buy time while transporting to a facility where surgical airway control is available." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Laundromat — 54-year-old male, cardiac arrest, V-fib, bystander CPR.", chief_complaint:"Refractory V-fib cardiac arrest, epinephrine indicated", scene_description:"A male collapsed in the parking lot. Bystander CPR in progress. One AED shock delivered. Your monitor shows V-fib still present after first shock. IV access established during CPR cycles. Epinephrine ready.", patient_info:"54-year-old male, PMH: unknown.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"V-fib",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"Refractory V-fib after one shock. CPR ongoing with good quality. IV access right AC established. Epinephrine 1mg IV administered. Downtime approximately 6 minutes total with continuous CPR.", teaching_points:"1. After first unsuccessful defibrillation continue CPR for 2 minutes then reassess — if V-fib persists defibrillate again and administer epinephrine 1mg IV; epinephrine increases myocardial perfusion pressure and may convert fine V-fib to a coarser waveform more responsive to defibrillation. 2. Amiodarone 300mg IV for refractory V-fib persisting after 3 shocks stabilizes the cardiac membrane — at the AEMT level know your protocol for amiodarone administration in cardiac arrest; it is one of your most powerful tools in refractory arrest." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Laundromat — 65-year-old male, severe hypothermia, temp 88°F, J-waves on monitor.", chief_complaint:"Severe hypothermia, near-absent respirations, J-waves", scene_description:"An elderly male who appears homeless is found unresponsive on a bench inside the 3 AM laundromat. He has wet clothing and was outside in 38°F weather. Temperature is 88.4°F. He has a faint pulse but nearly absent respirations.", patient_info:"Approximately 65-year-old male, PMH: unknown, suspected homelessness.", vitals:{bp:"76/44",hr:"38",rr:"5",spo2:"82%",gcs:"4",temp:"88.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Severe hypothermia at 88.4°F. Near-absent respirations at 5 per minute. Bradycardic at 38 bpm. SpO2 82%. GCS 4. Monitor shows sinus bradycardia with J-waves (Osborn waves) — classic hypothermia finding. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. J-waves (Osborn waves) on the 12-lead are pathognomonic for hypothermia — they appear as a positive deflection at the junction of the QRS and ST segment; their presence confirms hypothermic core temperature and warns of impending V-fib risk with rough handling. 2. Warmed IV fluids if available provide gentle internal rewarming — normal saline warmed to 40-42°C administered IV is safe; external warming with blankets, removed wet clothing, and a warm ambulance are also critical; handle gently to avoid triggering V-fib." },
],

bd_auto: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Auto Repair — male mechanic, bilateral crush injuries from car fall, shock.", chief_complaint:"Bilateral crush injury, hemorrhagic shock, crush syndrome risk", scene_description:"Fire freed the patient from under a vehicle that fell off a hydraulic lift. Both lower legs have severe crush injuries. He is in hemorrhagic shock. Two large bore IVs are established. Total entrapment time was approximately 12 minutes.", patient_info:"36-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"80/46",hr:"152",rr:"30",spo2:"95%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Bilateral lower extremity crush injuries. Hemorrhagic shock. IV x2 with NS running. Distal CSM absent in left foot. Right foot with diminished pulses. Crush syndrome risk with myoglobin release.", teaching_points:"1. Crush syndrome — rhabdomyolysis from muscle necrosis releases myoglobin, potassium, and uric acid into the bloodstream; high-volume IV fluid resuscitation (NS at 1-1.5 L/hr) is the treatment to prevent renal failure and cardiac arrhythmia from hyperkalemia. 2. Hyperkalemia from crush injury can cause fatal arrhythmias — place the patient on continuous cardiac monitoring and watch for peaked T-waves, widened QRS, and arrhythmias; transport immediately to a trauma center and communicate the mechanism and entrapment duration." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Auto Repair — 42-year-old mechanic, penetrating eye injury, irregular pupil.", chief_complaint:"Penetrating eye injury, globe rupture, D-shaped pupil", scene_description:"A mechanic was grinding without eye protection when a fragment struck his right eye. He cannot open the eye and is in significant pain. On examination with a penlight, the right pupil appears irregular — a D-shaped pupil suggesting globe rupture.", patient_info:"42-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"138/86",hr:"94",rr:"16",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Irregular D-shaped right pupil — highly concerning for globe rupture with iris herniation through the wound. Significant eye pain. Cannot open eye due to pain and blepharospasm. IV access established. IV fentanyl appropriate.", teaching_points:"1. An irregular D-shaped pupil after eye trauma is pathognomonic for globe rupture — apply a RIGID shield (Fox eye shield or paper cup) over the eye with NO pressure and patch both eyes; never apply direct pressure to a suspected globe rupture. 2. Keep the patient calm and still — increased intraocular pressure from straining, Valsalva, or anxiety can extrude vitreous humor through the wound; administer IV pain management per protocol and reassure the patient to avoid sudden movements." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Auto Repair — 63-year-old female, acute stroke in waiting room, 12-lead acquired.", chief_complaint:"Acute ischemic stroke, FAST positive, BP 204/118", scene_description:"A female customer began slurring her speech and dropped her coffee while waiting for her car. She has left facial droop, left arm weakness, and cannot speak clearly. Last known well is 25 minutes ago per her cell phone records.", patient_info:"63-year-old female, PMH: hypertension, Type 2 diabetes.", vitals:{bp:"204/118",hr:"88",rr:"16",spo2:"96%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"FAST positive — left facial droop, left arm drift, dysarthria. LKW 25 minutes ago. BG 118. BP 204/118. 12-lead shows no cardiac cause. IV access established. Stroke alert activated.", teaching_points:"1. Pre-hospital stroke alert with specific LKW time, stroke scale score, and blood glucose transmitted to the receiving stroke center reduces door-to-treatment time — call it in early with the Cincinnati or LAMS score to activate the stroke team before your arrival. 2. Do not attempt to lower the blood pressure — a BP of 204/118 in acute stroke may be the body's response to maintain cerebral perfusion around the clot; pre-hospital antihypertensives in stroke have been shown to worsen outcomes." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Auto Repair — 33-year-old male, refrigerant inhalation, bronchospasm, SpO2 91%.", chief_complaint:"Refrigerant inhalation, reactive airway bronchospasm", scene_description:"A mechanic was sprayed in the face with refrigerant from a ruptured AC line and ran outside. He has bilateral eye irritation and significant expiratory wheeze. SpO2 91% despite short exposure time. He has a history of mild asthma.", patient_info:"33-year-old male, PMH: mild asthma, uses albuterol PRN.", vitals:{bp:"130/80",hr:"112",rr:"28",spo2:"91%",gcs:"15",temp:"97.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Bilateral expiratory wheeze — refrigerant inhalation-induced bronchospasm on top of underlying asthma. SpO2 91%. Bilateral eye irritation. Skin redness on face and chest from cryogenic exposure. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Nebulized albuterol is the primary AEMT intervention for reactive airway bronchospasm — administer immediately; refrigerant inhalation combined with underlying asthma creates severe bronchospasm that requires bronchodilation and O2 supplementation. 2. Refrigerant skin and eye exposure requires simultaneous management — irrigate eyes with saline while administering the albuterol neb; have another crew member manage eye irrigation while you manage the airway." },
],

bd_club: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gentleman's Club — 22-year-old female, drug-facilitated assault, GHB suspected, respiratory depression.", chief_complaint:"Drug-facilitated assault, respiratory depression, GHB", scene_description:"Security brought a semi-conscious female to the entrance. She was conscious 45 minutes ago and had only 2 drinks. She is now unresponsive to voice and barely responds to pain. Breathing is slow and irregular at 8 per minute.", patient_info:"22-year-old female, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"82/48",hr:"108",rr:"8 irregular",spo2:"88%",gcs:"7",temp:"97.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Respiratory depression with SpO2 88%. GHB-like presentation — abrupt onset from alert to unresponsive with minimal alcohol reported. GHB has no reversal agent. Airway management is the primary intervention.", teaching_points:"1. GHB toxicity has no specific reversal agent — supportive care and airway management are the primary interventions; if BVM ventilation is maintaining adequate SpO2, continue and transport; if ventilation is inadequate, supraglottic airway placement is indicated. 2. This is a potential crime scene — preserve evidence, document everything objectively, and ensure police are notified; your patient care and evidence preservation must happen simultaneously." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gentleman's Club — 32-year-old male, zone 2 neck laceration, carotid hemorrhage.", chief_complaint:"Neck laceration, arterial hemorrhage, zone 2 injury", scene_description:"Police on scene. A male was cut with a broken bottle in zone 2 of the neck between the thyroid cartilage and angle of the jaw. Pulsatile bright red bleeding is present. An officer has been applying direct manual pressure.", patient_info:"32-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"90/56",hr:"142",rr:"26",spo2:"94%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Zone 2 neck laceration with pulsatile arterial hemorrhage. BP 90/56, HR 142 — early hemorrhagic shock. Large bore IV x2 established. Trachea midline. No expanding hematoma yet — monitor closely.", teaching_points:"1. Direct manual pressure is the ONLY appropriate hemorrhage control for neck vascular injury — never apply a circumferential neck bandage or tourniquet to the neck as it risks airway compression and bilateral carotid occlusion; use firm manual pressure directly over the wound site only. 2. An expanding neck hematoma is an airway emergency in development — as blood accumulates it can compress and deviate the trachea; monitor continuously for stridor, dyspnea, and tracheal deviation and transport immediately." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gentleman's Club — 51-year-old male, cocaine-associated ACS, anterior STEMI.", chief_complaint:"Cocaine ACS, anterior STEMI, hypertensive emergency", scene_description:"A 51-year-old male patron is diaphoretic with chest pain and admits to cocaine use approximately 1 hour ago. His 12-lead shows ST elevation in V1-V4 — anterior STEMI pattern. BP is critically elevated at 198/122.", patient_info:"51-year-old male, PMH: hypertension on amlodipine. Admits cocaine use.", vitals:{bp:"198/122",hr:"154",rr:"24",spo2:"95%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Anterior STEMI on 12-lead — V1-V4 ST elevation. BP 198/122. HR 154 — cocaine-driven sympathetic surge. Diaphoretic. Cocaine use within 1 hour. IV access established. Aspirin given.", teaching_points:"1. Beta blockers are CONTRAINDICATED in cocaine-associated ACS — they block beta receptors leaving alpha receptors unopposed, causing paradoxical hypertension and coronary vasospasm worsening the ischemia; do not give metoprolol or any beta blocker even if the tachycardia seems to demand it. 2. Anterior STEMI requires cath lab activation regardless of cocaine use — activate via 12-lead transmission; the ER will manage the cocaine component; your job is rapid transport with the 12-lead pre-notification." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gentleman's Club — 28-year-old female, fell from stage, spinal injury, neurogenic shock.", chief_complaint:"Fall from stage, paraplegia, neurogenic shock", scene_description:"A performer fell backward off a 4-foot stage and cannot feel or move her legs. She is conscious and terrified. Her BP is low and her HR is surprisingly slow for a trauma patient — consistent with neurogenic shock from spinal cord injury.", patient_info:"28-year-old female, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"84/50",hr:"52",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"97.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Neurogenic shock — hypotension WITH bradycardia (bradycardia distinguishes this from hemorrhagic shock). No external hemorrhage. Paraplegia — no movement or sensation below mid-thorax. Spinal precautions applied.", teaching_points:"1. Neurogenic shock differs from hemorrhagic shock — the bradycardia is the distinguishing feature; loss of sympathetic tone allows parasympathetic dominance causing bradycardia and vasodilation; atropine for bradycardia and cautious IV fluid resuscitation are appropriate. 2. Spinal immobilization and gentle patient packaging are critical — additional movement can convert an incomplete spinal injury to a complete one; use a scoop stretcher or long board with full spinal precautions and a minimum of 4 team members for log rolling." },
],

bd_bar: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tap Room — male, 45-year-old, respiratory failure, alcohol poisoning.", chief_complaint:"Alcohol poisoning, respiratory failure, airway compromise", scene_description:"A bar regular is unresponsive and slumped at the bar with vomitus in his airway. Respiratory rate is 5 per minute. He has a weak pulse. The bartender says he consumed at least 12 drinks over 6 hours.", patient_info:"45-year-old male, PMH: alcoholism. No other known PMH.", vitals:{bp:"88/50",hr:"50",rr:"5",spo2:"78%",gcs:"4",temp:"95.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Respiratory failure with vomitus in airway. SpO2 78%. Hypothermic at 95.8°F. GCS 4. BG 54 mg/dL — concurrent hypoglycemia. IV access established. Suction applied immediately.", teaching_points:"1. Suction and airway management are the immediate priorities — position, suction, jaw thrust, BVM ventilation; SpO2 of 78% is immediately life threatening; supraglottic airway if BVM ventilation is inadequate. 2. After establishing the airway administer D50 for BG of 54 mg/dL — alcohol inhibits hepatic gluconeogenesis causing hypoglycemia; D50 IV will correct the glucose and may contribute to improved LOC after airway is secured." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tap Room — 40-year-old male, blunt chest trauma, SpO2 88%, hemopneumothorax.", chief_complaint:"Multiple rib fractures, hemopneumothorax, SpO2 88%", scene_description:"A male took multiple kicks to the left chest wall during a bar fight. He has 4-5 left-sided rib fractures with guarding. SpO2 has declined from 97% to 88% over the past 8 minutes. Breath sounds are diminishing on the left.", patient_info:"40-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"122/78",hr:"110",rr:"28 shallow",spo2:"88%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Multiple left rib fractures with splinting. SpO2 declining to 88%. Diminishing breath sounds left lower lobe. No tracheal deviation. Not tension physiology yet. Developing hemopneumothorax from rib fractures.", teaching_points:"1. Declining SpO2 with multiple rib fractures and diminishing breath sounds suggests pneumothorax or hemopneumothorax — apply high-flow O2 via NRB, monitor for tension physiology (tracheal deviation, JVD, absent breath sounds), and prepare for possible needle decompression if the patient deteriorates. 2. CPAP may benefit isolated rib fracture pain-splinting without pneumothorax by improving tidal volume — use with caution if pneumothorax is suspected as CPAP can convert a simple pneumothorax to a tension pneumothorax." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tap Room — 61-year-old female, syncope, complete heart block, HR 38.", chief_complaint:"Complete heart block, syncope, transcutaneous pacing candidate", scene_description:"A female was found on the bathroom floor after syncope. She is profoundly bradycardic and hypotensive. She has afib and takes metoprolol. Her forehead has a contusion from falling. The monitor shows complete heart block.", patient_info:"61-year-old female, PMH: hypertension, afib. Takes Eliquis, metoprolol, lisinopril.", vitals:{bp:"78/46",hr:"38 irregular",rr:"14",spo2:"95%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Complete heart block — wide complex escape rhythm at 38 bpm. Hypotensive. Forehead contusion. On metoprolol which may be contributing to the block. Anticoagulated on Eliquis. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Complete heart block with hemodynamic compromise requires transcutaneous pacing at the AEMT level — atropine may be ineffective in complete heart block as the block is below the AV node; prepare pacing pads and transcutaneous pacemaker while establishing IV access. 2. Sedation and analgesia for transcutaneous pacing is important — TCP is extremely painful for a conscious patient; IV fentanyl per protocol before initiating pacing significantly improves patient tolerance and compliance with the procedure." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Tap Room — 23-year-old male, anaphylaxis, peanut exposure, stridor, BP 78/46.", chief_complaint:"Anaphylaxis, stridor, cardiovascular collapse, no EpiPen", scene_description:"A 23-year-old consumed bar mix containing peanuts without knowing. He developed urticaria and angioedema and is now in anaphylactic shock with audible stridor. His EpiPen was not with him. BP is critically low.", patient_info:"23-year-old male, PMH: severe peanut allergy, forgets his EpiPen.", vitals:{bp:"78/46",hr:"142",rr:"32",spo2:"88%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Anaphylactic shock with upper airway angioedema. Stridor audible. SpO2 88% and declining. BP 78/46 — distributive shock. GCS 13 from cerebral hypoperfusion. IV access established. Epinephrine drawn up.", teaching_points:"1. Epinephrine 0.3mg IM immediately addresses both the airway compromise and cardiovascular collapse — it causes vasoconstriction reversing distributive shock and mast cell stabilization stopping the allergic cascade; this is your most important intervention. 2. Large bore IV fluid bolus immediately after epi — 1 liter NS wide open is appropriate; if the patient does not respond to epi and fluids within 5 minutes, a second epi dose and ALS intercept for epinephrine infusion are indicated." },
],

bd_motel: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Motor Inn — room 14, found down x2 days, combined opioid and benzo OD, hypothermic.", chief_complaint:"Polysubstance OD, hypothermia, prolonged downtime, pressure sores", scene_description:"A male has been down for approximately 2 days. He is unresponsive with combined opioid and benzo OD. Temperature is 92°F. He has pressure sores developing at the sacrum. He has a faint pulse.", patient_info:"Approximately 38-year-old male, PMH: OUD, anxiety. Empty oxycodone and lorazepam bottles.", vitals:{bp:"78/42",hr:"46",rr:"4",spo2:"74%",gcs:"3",temp:"92.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Respiratory failure. SpO2 74%. Combined opioid and benzo OD — naloxone reverses opioid component only. Hypothermic at 92°F. Pressure sores at sacrum from prolonged downtime. J-waves on monitor.", teaching_points:"1. In combined opioid and benzodiazepine OD, naloxone reverses the opioid component but has no effect on benzodiazepine toxicity — the patient may have improved but still inadequate respirations after naloxone; supraglottic airway and BVM ventilation are required if respirations remain inadequate. 2. Rhabdomyolysis from prolonged compression is a serious secondary complication — the sacral pressure sore and 2-day downtime mean massive myoglobin release is likely; IV fluid resuscitation with cold saline addresses both rhabdo and hypothermia simultaneously." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Motor Inn — room 8, male hanging, cut down, pulseless, cervical spine injury.", chief_complaint:"Hanging, pulseless, cervical spine injury risk", scene_description:"A 42-year-old male was found hanging and cut down by his wife. He is pulseless and apneic on the bathroom floor. There is a deep circumferential ligature mark. Cervical spine injury from the hanging mechanism must be assumed. CPR started.", patient_info:"42-year-old male, PMH: depression, recently unemployed. Wife present.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"pulseless",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"97.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Pulseless and apneic. Deep ligature mark. Cyanosis. Cervical spine injury possible from hanging mechanism. Airway management with spinal precautions required simultaneously. CPR in progress. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Hanging victims require simultaneous spinal precautions and aggressive airway management — manual inline cervical stabilization while managing the airway is non-negotiable; the hanging mechanism can cause atlanto-occipital dislocation or cervical fracture. 2. Intubation in hanging victims may be challenging due to laryngeal trauma — fractured larynx or tracheal disruption can make standard airway management impossible; at the AEMT level supraglottic airway with inline stabilization is your best option if airway anatomy appears disrupted." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Motor Inn — room 22, 33-year-old female, suspected PE, S1Q3T3 on 12-lead.", chief_complaint:"Suspected pulmonary embolism, SpO2 88%, S1Q3T3", scene_description:"A female tourist who had a 14-hour car ride yesterday and uses OCPs is in severe respiratory distress. She has pleuritic right-sided chest pain, her right calf is swollen, and SpO2 88%. Her 12-lead shows S1Q3T3 pattern.", patient_info:"33-year-old female, PMH: OCP use. 14-hour car drive yesterday.", vitals:{bp:"102/66",hr:"132",rr:"36",spo2:"88%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Classic PE presentation — tachycardia, tachypnea, pleuritic chest pain, unilateral calf swelling, low SpO2, risk factors for PE. 12-lead shows sinus tachycardia with S1Q3T3 pattern. Large bore IV established.", teaching_points:"1. The S1Q3T3 pattern on 12-lead (prominent S wave in lead I, Q wave and T-wave inversion in lead III) is a classic but insensitive finding in PE — its presence in the right clinical context strongly supports your clinical diagnosis; document it and communicate it in your radio report. 2. High-flow O2 and positioning are your primary interventions — there is no field treatment for PE beyond supportive care; rapid transport to a facility with CT pulmonary angiography and anticoagulation capability is the goal." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Motor Inn — room 31, SIDS, 14-month-old, signs incompatible with resuscitation.", chief_complaint:"Infant found pulseless, lividity and rigor present", scene_description:"A 14-month-old was found unresponsive in her crib by parents. The child is pulseless, apneic, cold to touch, with dependent lividity on the back and early rigor. Temperature is 91°F. Parents are hysterical.", patient_info:"14-month-old female, PMH: healthy, up to date on vaccines.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"pulseless",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"91.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Dependent lividity, beginning rigor mortis, environmental temperature of 91°F — prolonged downtime incompatible with survival. No evidence of trauma. Parents hysterical. Law enforcement must be notified for mandatory investigation.", teaching_points:"1. Signs of obvious death (lividity, rigor, environmental temperature inconsistency) allow withholding resuscitation per medical director protocol — know your local protocol; calling a pediatric death is one of the most emotionally difficult moments in EMS but futile resuscitation is not in the family's best interest. 2. Family support and law enforcement coordination are as important as medical actions — designate one crew member to stay with the family away from the child, speak with compassion and honesty, and begin documentation for the mandatory law enforcement investigation." },
],

bd_suites: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Suites — lobby, male 47-year-old, multiple bee stings, anaphylactic shock.", chief_complaint:"Anaphylaxis, 30+ bee stings, cardiovascular collapse", scene_description:"A male guest was swarmed near the outdoor pool and sustained over 30 bee stings. He came inside and collapsed in the lobby. He is barely conscious, profoundly hypotensive, and developing angioedema. No prior bee allergy known.", patient_info:"47-year-old male, PMH: no known allergies. No EpiPen.", vitals:{bp:"68/36",hr:"148",rr:"32",spo2:"86%",gcs:"9",temp:"98.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Anaphylactic shock — profound hypotension, tachycardia, declining mentation, SpO2 86%. Multiple stings still embedded. Angioedema developing at lips. Large bore IV x2 established.", teaching_points:"1. This is the most severe form of anaphylaxis — epinephrine 0.3mg IM immediately, followed by large bore IV fluid bolus; if no improvement in 5 minutes, second epinephrine dose; if still no response, ALS intercept for epinephrine infusion may be required. 2. A patient this severely hypotensive from anaphylaxis needs aggressive IV fluid resuscitation — 1 liter NS wide open in combination with epinephrine; both address different components of anaphylactic shock simultaneously." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Suites — room 114, 54-year-old male, anterior STEMI, business traveler, missed medications.", chief_complaint:"Anterior STEMI, missed antihypertensives, business traveler", scene_description:"A business traveler called the front desk with chest pain. He is found in obvious distress, pale and diaphoretic. His 12-lead shows ST elevation in V1-V4 — anterior STEMI. He has not taken his blood pressure medication in 2 days.", patient_info:"54-year-old male, PMH: hypertension, hyperlipidemia. Takes atorvastatin and lisinopril.", vitals:{bp:"182/108",hr:"98",rr:"20",spo2:"95%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Anterior STEMI — ST elevation V1-V4. Diaphoretic and pale. SpO2 95%. No prior cardiac history. Has not taken lisinopril in 2 days — likely contributing to hypertension. IV access established. Aspirin given.", teaching_points:"1. Anterior STEMI indicates LAD occlusion — the LAD supplies a large portion of the left ventricle and anterior STEMIs carry higher mortality than inferior STEMIs; communicate urgency in your cath lab activation and document symptom onset time precisely. 2. IV access and aspirin are your two most impactful pre-hospital interventions for STEMI — aspirin's antiplatelet effect limits thrombus propagation; ensure the patient has not already taken aspirin today before giving 324mg PO." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Suites — pool area, 8-year-old submersion, near-drowning, CPR in progress.", chief_complaint:"Near-drowning, pediatric, inadequate respirations, hypothermic", scene_description:"A child was pulled from the pool and CPR was started by bystanders. He has a pulse now but remains unconscious with inadequate respirations requiring BVM ventilation. SpO2 86% improving with assisted ventilation. Hypothermic at 96.4°F.", patient_info:"8-year-old male, PMH: none, non-swimmer.", vitals:{bp:"92/56",hr:"122",rr:"6 inadequate",spo2:"86%",gcs:"6",temp:"96.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Post-submersion with inadequate respirations requiring BVM ventilation. SpO2 86% improving with BVM. Hypothermic at 96.4°F. Coarse crackles bilaterally from aspiration. Pulse restored. GCS 6.", teaching_points:"1. Near-drowning victims who are resuscitated are at high risk for secondary drowning (delayed pulmonary edema) over 4-24 hours — even a child who improves initially requires transport, hospital observation, and repeat assessment; all submersion victims are transported regardless of apparent recovery. 2. Supraglottic airway for a GCS of 6 with inadequate respirations in a pediatric submersion patient — it provides more reliable ventilation than BVM alone for transport and allows you to focus on other management." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Suites — room 308, 22-year-old female, status asthmaticus, silent chest, no inhaler.", chief_complaint:"Status asthmaticus, silent chest, pre-arrest, no medications", scene_description:"A female guest climbed three flights of stairs with the elevator broken, triggering a severe asthma attack. She has no inhaler available. She is in the room in tripod position, unable to speak at all, with a silent chest on auscultation.", patient_info:"22-year-old female, PMH: severe persistent asthma. Uses albuterol and budesonide. No inhaler available.", vitals:{bp:"128/80",hr:"128",rr:"36",spo2:"86%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Silent chest — critical finding; absence of wheeze indicates near-complete obstruction with minimal air movement. SpO2 86% and declining. GCS 14. Unable to speak. Pre-respiratory arrest.", teaching_points:"1. Silent chest asthma is a pre-arrest emergency requiring immediate nebulized albuterol — at the AEMT level this is your most critical intervention; administer back-to-back nebulizer treatments if SpO2 does not improve; contact medical direction for continuous albuterol neb consideration. 2. If the patient fatigues and SpO2 continues to decline despite neb treatment, begin assisting ventilations with BVM — slow gentle breaths are essential; too-rapid ventilation causes breath stacking (dynamic hyperinflation) which can cause a tension-like pneumothorax in severe asthma." },
],

bd_fire: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Fire Station 1 — off-duty firefighter, inferior STEMI with RV involvement, 52-year-old.", chief_complaint:"Inferior STEMI, RV infarction, nitrates contraindicated", scene_description:"An off-duty firefighter came in to help with equipment and mentioned chest pain. The on-duty crew noticed he was pale and sweating. His 12-lead shows obvious inferior STEMI with right-sided lead changes suggesting RV involvement.", patient_info:"52-year-old male, firefighter. PMH: hypertension, GERD. Takes lisinopril.", vitals:{bp:"172/106",hr:"96",rr:"20",spo2:"94%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Inferior STEMI — II, III, aVF elevation with reciprocal changes. Right-sided lead V4R shows ST elevation — RV infarction. Diaphoretic. IV access established. Aspirin given.", teaching_points:"1. RV infarction complicates inferior MI in approximately 40% of cases — RV infarction causes preload-dependent hemodynamics; nitrates, diuretics, and other preload-reducing agents can cause catastrophic hypotension; IV fluid is the treatment for hypotension in RV MI, not vasopressors initially. 2. Firefighters often minimize symptoms — treat the objective findings (diaphoresis, radiation, 12-lead changes) more than the subjective pain rating; a 52-year-old firefighter with these findings is having an ACS until proven otherwise." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Fire Station 1 — firefighter down, exertional heat stroke, temp 105.2°F.", chief_complaint:"Exertional heat stroke, altered mental status, aggressive cooling needed", scene_description:"A 29-year-old firefighter collapsed during live burn training in full gear. Fellow firefighters removed his SCBA and gear. He is confused, cannot state the date, and his skin is hot with minimal sweating. Temperature 105.2°F.", patient_info:"29-year-old male, in-service firefighter. PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"92/56",hr:"138",rr:"30",spo2:"97%",gcs:"12",temp:"105.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Exertional heat stroke — temperature 105.2°F with CNS dysfunction. Minimal sweating. Tachycardic and hypotensive. IV x2 established. Cold NS ready for IV cooling. Rhabdomyolysis risk high.", teaching_points:"1. Cold water immersion is the gold standard for exertional heat stroke if available — in the ambulance, cold IV saline, ice packs to axilla and groin, and maximum AC cooling are your tools; target temperature below 102°F within 30 minutes. 2. Aggressive IV fluid resuscitation with cold normal saline serves dual purposes — volume replacement for dehydration AND internal active cooling; run 1-2L of cold NS while applying external cooling simultaneously." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Fire Station 1 — civilian, 71-year-old male, acute stroke, drove himself, LKW 35 minutes.", chief_complaint:"Acute ischemic stroke, FAST positive, in tPA window", scene_description:"An elderly male drove himself to the fire station with stroke symptoms. He has left facial droop, left arm weakness, and slurred speech. Last known well is when he left home 35 minutes ago — he is within the tPA and thrombectomy treatment window.", patient_info:"71-year-old male, PMH: hypertension, diabetes.", vitals:{bp:"208/118",hr:"84",rr:"16",spo2:"97%",gcs:"13",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"FAST positive. LKW 35 minutes ago. BG 122. BP 208/118. IV access established. Stroke alert activated. Within 4.5-hour tPA window and 6-24 hour thrombectomy window.", teaching_points:"1. Pre-hospital stroke alert with LKW time, NIH stroke scale estimate, blood glucose, and absence of contraindications allows the stroke team to begin eligibility assessment before the patient arrives — call it in early to activate the team. 2. Do not attempt to lower the blood pressure in the field — a BP of 208/118 in acute stroke may be the body's response to maintain cerebral perfusion around the clot; pre-hospital antihypertensives in stroke worsen outcomes." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Fire Station 1 — probie, fall from ladder, axial load, calcaneus and lumbar injuries.", chief_complaint:"Axial load fall, calcaneus fracture, lumbar compression, neuro deficit", scene_description:"A probationary firefighter fell from the 3rd rung of a ground ladder landing on his feet. He has severe right heel pain and mid-lumbar spine pain. Decreased sensation in the right foot raises concern for nerve root involvement.", patient_info:"22-year-old male, probationary firefighter. PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"130/80",hr:"100",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Axial loading mechanism — calcaneus fracture right foot suspected with severe heel tenderness. Midline lumbar tenderness at L3-L4. Decreased right foot sensation. Ankle swelling and deformity. Distracting ankle injury.", teaching_points:"1. Axial load injuries from feet-first falls — always assess calcaneus, lumbar spine, AND wrists regardless of where the patient points to pain; the force transmits up the skeletal chain and causes injuries at multiple levels simultaneously. 2. Document neurological findings precisely with dermatomal distribution — decreased sensation in the right foot suggests L4-L5 nerve root involvement; this information guides the surgeon's urgency and operative approach at the receiving facility." },
],

bd_police: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy PD — prisoner, chest pain post-use of force, rib fractures, SpO2 91%.", chief_complaint:"Post-use of force chest trauma, pneumothorax developing", scene_description:"A 38-year-old male in custody is complaining of chest pain after a physical struggle during arrest. He has left-sided rib tenderness and his SpO2 has dropped to 91% with diminishing left breath sounds. Pneumothorax developing.", patient_info:"38-year-old male, in custody. PMH: unknown.", vitals:{bp:"142/88",hr:"118",rr:"28",spo2:"91%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Left lateral rib tenderness with diminishing breath sounds on the left. SpO2 91% declining. No tracheal deviation yet. Tachycardic. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. A prisoner in custody receives the same standard of care as any other patient — provide the same assessment, monitoring, interventions, and documentation regardless of the circumstances of their arrest. 2. Monitor closely for tension pneumothorax — if SpO2 continues to decline, tracheal deviation develops, or breath sounds become absent, needle decompression at 2nd ICS midclavicular line on the left is indicated; do not wait for all classic signs of tension to develop before acting." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy PD — officer, airbag deployment, sternal fracture, myocardial contusion possible.", chief_complaint:"Airbag injury, sternal fracture, cardiac monitoring needed", scene_description:"A police officer crashed during a pursuit. Airbags deployed. He has significant anterior chest pain and SpO2 94%. He was in full duty uniform with a ballistic vest. 12-lead acquired — sinus tachycardia with possible ST changes.", patient_info:"34-year-old male police officer. PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"136/86",hr:"108",rr:"22",spo2:"94%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Sternal tenderness and possible fracture from airbag. Bilateral anterior rib tenderness. SpO2 94% declining. 12-lead shows sinus tachycardia with minor ST changes — monitoring for myocardial contusion or commotio cordis pattern.", teaching_points:"1. Blunt precordial trauma can cause myocardial contusion — monitor 12-lead for ST changes, new bundle branch block, or arrhythmias; these indicate myocardial injury requiring continuous cardiac monitoring en route. 2. Ballistic vests protect against penetrating trauma but transmit and distribute blunt force broadly — always remove or open the vest to properly assess the chest wall; the vest may prevent penetrating injury while causing extensive rib and sternal fractures." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy PD — records clerk, cardiac arrest, PEA rhythm, SAH etiology suspected.", chief_complaint:"Non-traumatic PEA arrest, SAH etiology, H's and T's assessment", scene_description:"A 48-year-old records clerk who had a severe headache all morning was found slumped at her desk pulseless. Monitor shows PEA rhythm at 40 bpm. Coworkers say she had the worst headache of her life starting 2 hours ago.", patient_info:"48-year-old female, PMH: hypertension on lisinopril.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"PEA 40 bpm",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"PEA cardiac arrest. SAH-induced arrest suspected based on prodromal thunderclap headache. IV access established. CPR ongoing with good quality.", teaching_points:"1. PEA cardiac arrest requires systematic H's and T's assessment — for this patient consider hypovolemia from SAH, hypoxia, and thrombosis; treat reversible causes while maintaining high-quality CPR without interruption. 2. Epinephrine 1mg IV every 3-5 minutes is appropriate in PEA arrest — it increases coronary and cerebral perfusion pressure during CPR; combined with high-quality compressions and identifying reversible causes it represents your complete algorithm for PEA." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy PD — holding cell, 26-year-old, fentanyl OD, respiratory arrest, pre-cardiac arrest.", chief_complaint:"High-potency fentanyl OD, respiratory arrest, IO access needed", scene_description:"A prisoner is in respiratory arrest in a holding cell from suspected fentanyl concealed on his person. Heart rate is present but fading rapidly. 4mg IN naloxone given with minimal response. Suspected high-potency fentanyl analogue.", patient_info:"26-year-old male, PMH: OUD. In custody.", vitals:{bp:"72/38",hr:"38",rr:"0 apneic",spo2:"62%",gcs:"3",temp:"97.0°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Respiratory arrest — apneic. SpO2 62%. HR 38 — pre-cardiac arrest. Pinpoint pupils. BVM ventilation initiated. IO access established. Naloxone 4mg IN administered with minimal response.", teaching_points:"1. BVM ventilation is the most important intervention — a ventilated patient without a heartbeat is still alive; naloxone is adjunctive; ventilate first, every time, without exception. 2. High-potency fentanyl analogues may require extremely high naloxone doses — if 4mg IN has not restored respirations, additional IV/IO naloxone up to 10mg may be needed per protocol; ventilation keeps the patient alive while naloxone takes effect." },
],

bd_school: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy High School — 16-year-old football player, first seizure on field, helmeted.", chief_complaint:"New onset seizure, helmeted athlete, IV access needed", scene_description:"A football player seized during practice for 2 minutes and is now post-ictal. His helmet is still on. The coach is holding his head. Temperature is slightly elevated. No prior seizure history. IV access needed for potential repeat seizure.", patient_info:"16-year-old male, PMH: no seizure history. Football player.", vitals:{bp:"130/82",hr:"116",rr:"16",spo2:"97%",gcs:"11",temp:"99.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Post-ictal GCS 11. First-time seizure. Helmet in place. Slightly febrile. BG 88 mg/dL. IV access established. 12-lead shows sinus tachycardia.", teaching_points:"1. For a helmeted athlete remove the face mask but leave the helmet in place unless full airway access is required — the helmet and shoulder pads work together to maintain neutral spinal alignment; removing the helmet without the shoulder pads creates cervical extension. 2. IV access in a post-ictal patient is appropriate at the AEMT level — if the patient seizes again, IV lorazepam or diazepam is your first-line treatment; establishing access while post-ictal avoids the difficulty of IV placement during an active seizure." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy High School — teacher, 44-year-old, anaphylaxis, epi given by nurse, biphasic risk.", chief_complaint:"First-time anaphylaxis, epinephrine given, monitoring needed", scene_description:"A 44-year-old teacher had an anaphylactic reaction from an unknown allergen. The school nurse administered epinephrine 8 minutes ago. She has improved but still has residual wheeze and hives. Biphasic reaction is possible.", patient_info:"44-year-old female, PMH: no known allergies. First anaphylaxis.", vitals:{bp:"118/72",hr:"114",rr:"22",spo2:"96%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Improving but not resolved anaphylaxis post-epinephrine. Residual urticaria and wheeze. SpO2 96%. Tachycardic. IV access established. Epinephrine effect may be wearing off — reassess every 5 minutes.", teaching_points:"1. Epinephrine has a short half-life of 10-20 minutes — continued monitoring is essential as the anaphylactic mediators outlast the epinephrine; a second dose may be needed and is appropriate per protocol if symptoms return. 2. Nebulized albuterol addresses the bronchospasm component that epinephrine may incompletely resolve — administer if wheeze persists after epinephrine; it directly bronchodilates the airways without the cardiovascular effects of repeat epinephrine." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy High School — 14-year-old, fentanyl OD in bathroom, respiratory arrest.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric fentanyl OD, respiratory arrest, weight-based naloxone", scene_description:"A 14-year-old student is found unresponsive in the boys' bathroom with suspected fentanyl. He is apneic. A school resource officer has started rescue breathing. SpO2 62% improving with assisted ventilation. IO access being established.", patient_info:"14-year-old male, PMH: unknown. Weight approximately 55 kg.", vitals:{bp:"82/48",hr:"52",rr:"0 apneic",spo2:"62%",gcs:"3",temp:"97.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Respiratory arrest. SpO2 62% improving with BVM. Pinpoint pupils. HR 52. Naloxone 2mg IN administered by SRO. IV/IO access being established.", teaching_points:"1. Weight-based naloxone in adolescents — for a 55kg teenager adult dosing of 0.4-2mg IV/IO/IN is appropriate; if initial IN dose has not restored respirations within 2-3 minutes, administer IV/IO naloxone; fentanyl's potency often requires multiple doses. 2. This is a crime scene involving a minor — document all findings objectively, secure the drug evidence for law enforcement, and follow mandatory reporting requirements; your clinical documentation may be used in both medical and legal proceedings." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy High School — 15-year-old female, choking, progressing to complete obstruction.", chief_complaint:"Choking, progressing from partial to complete obstruction, laryngoscopy may be needed", scene_description:"A 15-year-old choked on food in the cafeteria. Partial obstruction has progressed — she can no longer cough effectively, cannot speak, and SpO2 is declining to 84%. Abdominal thrusts by a lunch monitor have not cleared the obstruction.", patient_info:"15-year-old female, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"120/74",hr:"122",rr:"labored no cough",spo2:"84%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Complete airway obstruction now. Unable to cough or speak. SpO2 84% and declining. Cyanosis developing. Abdominal thrusts not successful after multiple attempts. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Continue back blows and abdominal thrusts while the patient is conscious — if they become unconscious, begin CPR and look in the airway with every ventilation attempt; at the AEMT level laryngoscopy with Magill forceps to directly visualize and remove the foreign body is the definitive intervention. 2. If laryngoscopy fails and SpO2 continues to fall, notify ALS for potential surgical airway — at the AEMT level continue BVM ventilation attempts around the obstruction; communication of urgency to ALS is critical." },
],

bd_church: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's House of Grace — 78-year-old male, V-fib cardiac arrest during Sunday service.", chief_complaint:"V-fib cardiac arrest, large crowd, AED in hallway", scene_description:"An elderly male collapsed in his pew during Sunday service. Nurse congregant performing CPR. AED is in the hallway 30 feet away. Approximately 200 parishioners present. Your unit arrives 4 minutes post-collapse.", patient_info:"78-year-old male, PMH: unknown, heart problems per wife.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"V-fib on monitor",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"V-fib on monitor. CPR 4 minutes ongoing by trained bystander. AED available. Large crowd in confined space. IV access established during CPR cycles.", teaching_points:"1. Crowd management in a church is an operational priority — designate one team member specifically to manage bystanders and create a work space; ineffective CPR due to lack of working space is a preventable cause of poor outcomes in public cardiac arrest. 2. Epinephrine 1mg IV every 3-5 minutes after the second defibrillation attempt — at the AEMT level epinephrine increases coronary perfusion pressure during compressions making subsequent defibrillation more likely to succeed." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's House of Grace — 82-year-old female, hip fracture from kneeling, IV analgesia needed.", chief_complaint:"Hip fracture from kneeling, severe pain, anticoagulated patient", scene_description:"An 82-year-old woman fractured her left hip while kneeling in prayer. She has classic external rotation and shortening. She is in severe pain 9/10 and on warfarin. IV access established.", patient_info:"82-year-old female, PMH: osteoporosis, afib. Takes warfarin and metoprolol.", vitals:{bp:"158/90",hr:"96 irregular",rr:"18",spo2:"97%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Classic hip fracture — external rotation, shortening, severe groin pain. Distal CSM intact. On warfarin — elevated bleeding risk significantly. IV access established. Pain 9/10.", teaching_points:"1. IV fentanyl for pain management in elderly hip fracture — start at 0.5 mcg/kg in patients over 70 and titrate slowly; elderly patients have reduced renal and hepatic clearance resulting in prolonged drug effect and increased respiratory depression risk. 2. Document CSM before and after packaging — immobilization with a scoop stretcher can cause position changes that affect vascular and nerve function; always reassess and document distal function after every position change." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's House of Grace — 6-year-old, prolonged febrile seizure 7 minutes, IV diazepam needed.", chief_complaint:"Prolonged febrile seizure, status epilepticus, benzodiazepine needed", scene_description:"A 6-year-old boy has been actively seizing for 7 minutes during the children's program. Temperature is 104.2°F. He is on amoxicillin for an ear infection. He is still in active tonic-clonic activity with SpO2 94% declining.", patient_info:"6-year-old male, PMH: otitis media on amoxicillin. No seizure history.", vitals:{bp:"116/70",hr:"136",rr:"20 irregular",spo2:"94%",gcs:"3 seizing",temp:"104.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Active tonic-clonic seizure at 7 minutes — status epilepticus. Febrile at 104.2°F. SpO2 94% declining. IV access established during seizure with difficulty.", teaching_points:"1. Lorazepam 0.1mg/kg IV is first line for status epilepticus in AEMT scope — for this child approximately 2.5-3mg IV; IN midazolam 0.2mg/kg is an alternative if IV cannot be established; administer and monitor respiratory status carefully after administration. 2. Cooling measures should be initiated simultaneously — remove clothing, apply cool wet cloths to the neck, axilla, and groin; febrile seizure recurrence risk decreases as temperature decreases; cooling and benzodiazepines work together." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's House of Grace — 34-year-old female minister, syncope, 32 weeks pregnant, fell from pulpit.", chief_complaint:"Third trimester syncope, fall, abdominal trauma, abruption risk", scene_description:"A 34-year-old minister at 32 weeks gestation fainted and fell forward from the pulpit, striking her abdomen on the platform edge. She is now alert but hypotensive, tachycardic, and has increasing abdominal pain. Uterus is tender.", patient_info:"34-year-old female, G1P0, 32 weeks pregnant. PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"82/50",hr:"116",rr:"22",spo2:"98%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Hypotensive and tachycardic pregnant patient at 32 weeks after abdominal trauma. Uterine tenderness and rigidity between contractions — placental abruption likely. Chin laceration controlled. IV x2 large bore established.", teaching_points:"1. Placental abruption can cause concealed hemorrhage of 1-2 liters into the uterine cavity with minimal external bleeding — uterine rigidity and maternal shock despite no visible bleeding confirms significant internal hemorrhage requiring immediate surgical intervention. 2. Large bore IV x2 with NS resuscitation to maintain systolic above 90 mmHg plus left lateral positioning for transport — every minute of maternal hypotension reduces uteroplacental perfusion; communicate 32-week gestation and suspected abruption on your radio report to activate the OB team." },
],

bd_park: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Deron's Dreamland Park — 34-year-old male, Colles fracture, IV analgesia, morphine allergy.", chief_complaint:"Distal radius fracture, IV fentanyl needed, morphine allergic", scene_description:"A male fell off a park bench and caught himself with his outstretched right hand. His wrist is visibly deformed with swelling. Pain rated 9/10. IV access established. Reports a morphine allergy causing nausea and vomiting.", patient_info:"34-year-old male, PMH: morphine allergy (nausea/vomiting). No other PMH.", vitals:{bp:"130/82",hr:"98",rr:"16",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Distal radius deformity — Colles fracture. Distal CSM intact. IV access established in left AC. Pain 9/10. No open wound.", teaching_points:"1. Fentanyl 1 mcg/kg IV is appropriate when morphine allergy is reported — it is synthetic with no cross-reactivity to morphine in most cases; administer slowly over 3 minutes and titrate to effect while monitoring respiratory status. 2. Document pre and post-splinting CSM — apply padded posterior long arm splint; if the patient reports increased numbness after splinting, loosen immediately and reassess distal function." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Deron's Dreamland Park — 43-year-old female, heat exhaustion, near-syncope, IV hydration needed.", chief_complaint:"Heat exhaustion, near-syncope, IV rehydration candidate", scene_description:"A 43-year-old jogger nearly lost consciousness on her third lap. Temperature 102.6°F, hot moist skin, tachycardic, mildly hypotensive. Takes a diuretic for hypertension and brought no water. IV access established.", patient_info:"43-year-old female, PMH: hypertension on hydrochlorothiazide.", vitals:{bp:"94/58",hr:"122",rr:"22",spo2:"98%",gcs:"15",temp:"102.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Heat exhaustion with near-syncope. Hot moist skin. Diuretic use worsening dehydration. Tachycardic and mildly hypotensive. IV access established in right AC.", teaching_points:"1. IV normal saline 500mL to 1L bolus and reassess — IV fluid replaces volume AND provides mild internal cooling; oral fluids are only appropriate for fully alert patients who are not near-syncopal and can swallow safely. 2. Cool wet cloths to axilla and neck while running IV fluids — move the patient into the cool ambulance and monitor temperature continuously; reassess after fluid bolus to distinguish simple dehydration from more serious pathology." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Deron's Dreamland Park — 8-year-old, stick to right eye, globe rupture suspected, IV pain management.", chief_complaint:"Penetrating eye injury, globe rupture, D-shaped pupil", scene_description:"An 8-year-old ran into a branch in the wooded section of the park and struck his right eye. He has an irregular right pupil and subconjunctival hemorrhage. Periorbital swelling developing. Crying and will not open the eye.", patient_info:"8-year-old male, PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"106/64",hr:"108",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Irregular D-shaped right pupil — possible globe rupture with iris herniation. Subconjunctival hemorrhage. Periorbital swelling. Significant pain. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. Rigid eye shield with NO pressure is mandatory — a paper cup secured with tape around the orbit not touching the eye is appropriate field management; no direct pressure ever on a possible globe injury. 2. IV fentanyl reduces pain without increasing intraocular pressure — a calm comfortable patient is less likely to rub or squeeze the injured eye during transport; titrate to effect and monitor respiratory status." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Deron's Dreamland Park — 76-year-old male, hip fracture, anticoagulated, IV analgesia needed.", chief_complaint:"Hip fracture, warfarin patient, IV fentanyl needed", scene_description:"An elderly male tripped on an uneven paving stone on the walking path and fell on his right side. Right leg externally rotated and shortened. Pain 9/10. Cannot move without severe worsening. On warfarin for atrial fibrillation.", patient_info:"76-year-old male, PMH: osteoporosis, afib. Takes warfarin and metoprolol.", vitals:{bp:"150/90",hr:"84 irregular",rr:"18",spo2:"96%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Classic hip fracture — external rotation and shortening. Distal CSM intact. On warfarin — elevated hemorrhage risk. Afib on monitor. IV access established. Pain 9/10.", teaching_points:"1. IV fentanyl 0.5 mcg/kg in this 76-year-old and titrate to effect — adequate analgesia reduces sympathetic activation, lowers heart rate and blood pressure, and makes packaging significantly safer for the patient. 2. Communicate warfarin use and last INR dose to the ER — warfarin reversal may be needed before surgical repair; document anticoagulant details explicitly in your radio report and your PCR." },
],

bd_mhp: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Mobile Home Park, Lot 14 — male, 54-year-old, severe COPD exacerbation, CPAP candidate.", chief_complaint:"COPD exacerbation, SpO2 84%, CPAP and neb treatment", scene_description:"A 54-year-old male with severe COPD is in his recliner in critical respiratory distress. His O2 concentrator has been unplugged. The trailer is filled with cigarette smoke. His wife is frantic. Access to the patient is tight through the cluttered interior.", patient_info:"54-year-old male, PMH: severe COPD, CHF, hypertension, smoker x35 years.", vitals:{bp:"162/96",hr:"114",rr:"32",spo2:"84%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"SpO2 84% — critical hypoxia. Tripod positioning, accessory muscle use, prolonged expiration. Bilateral expiratory wheeze. Barrel chest. IV access established. CPAP kit prepared. Dual bronchodilator neb ready.", teaching_points:"1. CPAP is your primary AEMT intervention for severe COPD exacerbation — apply at 5-10 cmH2O with O2 titrated to maintain SpO2 88-92%; it reduces work of breathing and prevents respiratory failure; set it up immediately while packaging the patient. 2. Nebulized albuterol and ipratropium through the CPAP circuit treats bronchospasm simultaneously — dual-drug neb through CPAP is more effective than either alone in acute COPD exacerbation." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Mobile Home Park, Lot 22 — 78-year-old female found down x3 days, sepsis and hypoglycemia.", chief_complaint:"Found down, septic shock, BG 42, D50 and IV fluids", scene_description:"A 78-year-old diabetic female is found on her bathroom floor after 3 days. She is febrile, hypoglycemic, and in septic shock. IV access is needed for D50 and fluid resuscitation. The home is extremely warm making her hyperthermia worse.", patient_info:"78-year-old female, PMH: diabetes, hypertension, lives alone.", vitals:{bp:"82/48",hr:"118",rr:"22",spo2:"90%",gcs:"6",temp:"103.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"GCS 6. BG 42 mg/dL. Septic shock — febrile, tachycardic, hypotensive. Pressure sores at sacrum. Signs of prolonged dehydration. IV access established. D50 and NS bolus both indicated simultaneously.", teaching_points:"1. Treat D50 and septic shock fluid resuscitation simultaneously — D50 0.5g/kg IV for the critical hypoglycemia while running NS wide open for the septic shock; both are immediately life-threatening and must be treated together. 2. Pre-notification for sepsis — communicate your suspicion of sepsis with estimated temperature, hypotension, and altered mental status from baseline in your radio report; early goal-directed therapy in the ER begins with your pre-notification." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Mobile Home Park, Lot 7 — 4-year-old, opioid and benzo ingestion, IO access needed.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric polysubstance ingestion, respiratory depression, IO access", scene_description:"A 4-year-old who ingested his mother's oxycodone and alprazolam is barely responsive with respiratory depression. SpO2 84% with BVM. IV access has failed twice. IO access at the proximal tibia is indicated for naloxone and glucose administration.", patient_info:"4-year-old male, PMH: none. Weight approximately 16kg.", vitals:{bp:"82/48",hr:"58",rr:"6",spo2:"84%",gcs:"5",temp:"97.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Combined opioid and benzodiazepine ingestion with respiratory failure. SpO2 84% improving with BVM. Pinpoint pupils. IV failed x2. IO proximal tibia established. BG 48 — concurrent hypoglycemia.", teaching_points:"1. IO access after two failed IV attempts in a critically ill child — proximal tibial IO provides immediate vascular access for naloxone, dextrose, and fluid resuscitation; do not delay further with IV attempts when a child is in respiratory failure. 2. Benzodiazepine co-ingestion means naloxone only partially reverses the respiratory depression — after naloxone the opioid component improves but benzodiazepine depression remains; airway management with BVM or supraglottic airway may still be needed even after naloxone administration." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Mobile Home Park, Lot 31 — domestic violence, 28-year-old female, forearm fracture, IV fentanyl.", chief_complaint:"Domestic violence, forearm fracture, IV pain management", scene_description:"A 28-year-old postpartum female has a forearm fracture from domestic assault. Police on scene. She is in significant pain and tachycardic. IV access established. Fentanyl analgesia is appropriate and needed for patient cooperation with assessment.", patient_info:"28-year-old female, PMH: none. 6 weeks postpartum.", vitals:{bp:"138/90",hr:"112",rr:"18",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Right forearm deformity — fracture confirmed. Distal CSM intact. Periorbital hematoma. Tachycardic from pain and anxiety. IV access established in left AC. Fentanyl 1 mcg/kg IV appropriate.", teaching_points:"1. IV fentanyl 1 mcg/kg for pain management in a postpartum patient — fentanyl is appropriate and postpartum status does not significantly alter your dosing; adequate analgesia reduces stress response and makes the patient more cooperative with assessment and splinting. 2. Document everything objectively in domestic violence calls — body diagram of injury locations, patient's own words in quotes, mechanism reported; your PCR is a legal document and may be subpoenaed in criminal proceedings." },
],

bd_nursing: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Grand-daddy's Nursing and Rehab — room 12, male, septic shock, IV fluids, 12-lead acquired.", chief_complaint:"Septic shock from UTI, IV fluid resuscitation, 12-lead", scene_description:"A 79-year-old male nursing home resident has acute AMS from his baseline with septic shock physiology from a suspected UTI. He is hypotensive and tachycardic. IV access and fluid resuscitation are needed. A 12-lead should be acquired to rule out cardiac cause of AMS.", patient_info:"79-year-old male, PMH: hypertension, Type 2 DM, afib. On warfarin.", vitals:{bp:"88/54",hr:"108 irregular",rr:"22",spo2:"93%",gcs:"12",temp:"101.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Septic shock — hypotensive, tachycardic, febrile, altered from baseline. Afib on monitor. SpO2 93%. Anticoagulated on warfarin. IV access established. NS 500mL bolus running. 12-lead shows afib with no acute ST changes.", teaching_points:"1. Sepsis fluid resuscitation — 30mL/kg NS bolus per Surviving Sepsis guidelines; for a 70kg patient that is 2100mL; in the field give 500mL-1L and reassess; in an elderly CHF patient be cautious with aggressive fluids as pulmonary edema can develop rapidly. 2. A 12-lead in septic AMS rules out a cardiac cause — ACS can present as AMS in elderly patients; a 12-lead showing no ST changes with a clinical picture of infection confirms your sepsis diagnosis and guides treatment." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Grand-daddy's Nursing and Rehab — room 24, hip fracture, IV fentanyl, DNR confirmed, Eliquis noted.", chief_complaint:"Hip fracture, behavioral pain assessment, IV fentanyl, DNR", scene_description:"An 84-year-old female with moderate dementia has a hip fracture after a fall from bed. DNR is confirmed. She cannot verbally rate her pain but shows significant behavioral pain cues. IV access established. Fentanyl analgesia appropriate.", patient_info:"84-year-old female, PMH: osteoporosis, afib, dementia. Takes Eliquis.", vitals:{bp:"148/90",hr:"92 irregular",rr:"18",spo2:"96%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Hip fracture confirmed — external rotation, shortening. DNR present and valid. Moderate dementia. Behavioral pain cues: grimacing, guarding, resistance to movement. On Eliquis — bleeding risk elevated. IV access established.", teaching_points:"1. IV fentanyl 0.5 mcg/kg starting dose in an elderly demented patient — titrate based on behavioral response (reduced grimacing, guarding, and agitation); the PAINAD behavioral pain scale guides dosing in non-verbal patients. 2. Eliquis communication to the ER is critical — anticoagulant name, dose, and last dose time must be in your radio report; the orthopedic surgeon needs INR equivalent information before planning any surgical fixation." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Grand-daddy's Nursing and Rehab — room 8, aspiration, DNI confirmed, CPAP applied, SpO2 improving.", chief_complaint:"Aspiration with SpO2 86%, DNI order, CPAP appropriate", scene_description:"A 72-year-old male with stroke-related dysphagia aspirated during lunch. SpO2 86% with DNI confirmed. CPAP has been applied as the ceiling of non-surgical airway intervention. SpO2 is improving to 91% with CPAP and aggressive suctioning.", patient_info:"72-year-old male, PMH: CVA, dysphagia, COPD. DNI order confirmed.", vitals:{bp:"152/94",hr:"114",rr:"28",spo2:"91% on CPAP",gcs:"12",temp:"100.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Aspiration with improving SpO2 on CPAP. DNI confirmed — no intubation. Coarse crackles right lower lobe. Food particles cleared from oropharynx with yankauer. CPAP at 8 cmH2O maintaining SpO2 91%.", teaching_points:"1. CPAP does not violate a DNI order — a DNI specifically prohibits endotracheal intubation; non-invasive ventilation including CPAP is generally not covered by a DNI unless the order specifically states it; clarify with the order and medical direction if uncertain. 2. Suction before CPAP application in aspiration — clearing aspirated material from the oropharynx before applying CPAP prevents forcing material deeper into the airway; aggressive yankauer suctioning is always the first step in aspiration management." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Grand-daddy's Nursing and Rehab — room 19, cardiac arrest, valid DNR located, resuscitation stopped, family conflict.", chief_complaint:"Cardiac arrest, valid DNR confirmed, CPR stopped, family conflict", scene_description:"An 86-year-old female in cardiac arrest had CPR started by staff. The valid DNR has now been confirmed and CPR has been stopped per protocol. The patient's daughter has arrived demanding CPR be restarted. Staff confirm the DNR is valid and reflects the patient's long-standing wishes.", patient_info:"86-year-old female, PMH: end-stage CHF, COPD, dementia. Valid DNR confirmed.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"pulseless",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"Cardiac arrest. Valid DNR confirmed with document number and signature. CPR stopped per protocol. Family member demanding CPR restart. Medical direction contacted.", teaching_points:"1. A valid DNR is a legal document reflecting the patient's wishes — family members do not have the authority to override a valid patient-signed DNR; calmly explain that you are honoring the patient's own documented wishes; contact medical direction for support if family conflict escalates. 2. Comfort-focused language in family conflict: 'I understand how devastating this is. Your mother signed this document because she wanted to make her own decision about this moment. We are honoring what she chose for herself.' Stay calm and give family time to process." },
],

bd_estates: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, 142 Estates Drive, Big Daddy Estates — 72-year-old male, severe respiratory distress, CHF exacerbation, IV access needed.", chief_complaint:"Acute CHF exacerbation, flash pulmonary edema, CPAP and IV indicated", scene_description:"A 72-year-old male is sitting bolt upright in his recliner unable to speak in full sentences. His wife says he has been worsening for two days and could not lie flat last night. Crackles are audible from the doorway.", patient_info:"72-year-old male, PMH: CHF EF 25%, hypertension, atrial fibrillation. Takes furosemide 80mg, lisinopril, carvedilol, digoxin.", vitals:{bp:"196/114",hr:"104 irregular",rr:"32",spo2:"82%",gcs:"15",temp:"98.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Bilateral crackles to apices — flash pulmonary edema. JVD at 45 degrees. Massive peripheral edema. SpO2 82% on room air. Cannot complete a sentence. Weight up 14 lbs this week per wife. Orthopnea confirmed.", teaching_points:"1. CPAP at 5-10 cmH2O is your highest-yield intervention in flash pulmonary edema — it reduces preload, decreases work of breathing, and improves oxygenation; apply early and titrate to SpO2 above 94%. 2. IV access in CHF exacerbation — establish large bore IV; nitroglycerin SL or spray reduces preload rapidly if systolic BP is above 90 mmHg; do not give furosemide without confirming it is in your scope and medical control approval." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, 87 Crown Estates Court — 4-year-old, status epilepticus, still seizing on arrival, benzodiazepine needed.", chief_complaint:"Pediatric status epilepticus, active seizure 7 minutes, IN midazolam", scene_description:"A 4-year-old has been actively seizing for 7 minutes with a temperature of 104.2°F. The child is in tonic-clonic activity on the kitchen floor. The mother is hysterical. SpO2 is 92% and dropping. IV access in a seizing child will be extremely difficult.", patient_info:"4-year-old male, 18kg, PMH: one prior febrile seizure. No seizure medications.", vitals:{bp:"not obtained",hr:"156",rr:"irregular",spo2:"92%",gcs:"3 seizing",temp:"104.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Active tonic-clonic status epilepticus at 7 minutes. Febrile at 104.2°F. SpO2 92% declining. IV access nearly impossible in actively seizing child. Jaw clenched.", teaching_points:"1. IN midazolam 0.2mg/kg is your first-line intervention in a seizing child where IV access is not available — for this 18kg child that is approximately 3.6mg IN divided between nostrils; onset is 3-5 minutes; it is as effective as IV diazepam for pediatric seizures. 2. If IV access can be established, lorazepam 0.1mg/kg IV is first line — for this child approximately 1.8mg IV; have the BVM ready as benzodiazepines will reduce respiratory drive after seizure cessation." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, 310 Estates Drive — 58-year-old female, prolonged fall, 12 hours down, rhabdomyolysis suspected, IV access needed.", chief_complaint:"Prolonged immobility, rhabdomyolysis risk, IV fluid resuscitation", scene_description:"A 58-year-old diabetic female has been on the bathroom floor for approximately 12 hours. She is alert but weak and dehydrated. Dark urine is visible. Pressure injury forming on her right flank. Her muscles are diffusely tender.", patient_info:"58-year-old female, PMH: obesity, Type 2 diabetes, hypertension. Takes metformin, lisinopril.", vitals:{bp:"148/94",hr:"110",rr:"18",spo2:"96%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Prolonged down time approximately 12 hours. Diffuse muscle tenderness. Dark tea-colored urine visible — myoglobinuria suggests rhabdomyolysis. Dehydrated with dry mucous membranes. External rotation right hip — possible fracture. BG 218 mg/dL.", teaching_points:"1. Rhabdomyolysis requires aggressive IV fluid resuscitation to protect the kidneys — start NS at 1L/hour or per protocol and communicate downtime precisely to the ER. 2. Blood glucose of 218 in a diabetic after 12 hours without food reflects stress hyperglycemia — monitor but do not treat in the field; the more urgent concerns are rhabdomyolysis and the possible hip fracture." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, 45 Big Daddy Estates Blvd — 16-year-old male, opioid overdose, partial naloxone response, continued respiratory depression.", chief_complaint:"Teenage polypharmacy overdose, partial reversal, IV access and repeat naloxone", scene_description:"A 16-year-old was found by his friend after taking oxycodone from a parent's prescription and drinking alcohol. 4mg IN naloxone was given en route by first responders. GCS has improved from 4 to 8 but respirations remain inadequate at 8/min and SpO2 is 84%.", patient_info:"16-year-old male, PMH: unknown. Oxycodone ingestion plus alcohol.", vitals:{bp:"100/62",hr:"60",rr:"8",spo2:"84%",gcs:"8",temp:"97.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Partial naloxone response — improved but still in respiratory failure. SpO2 84%, RR 8. Pupils partially improved from pinpoint. IV access being established. Alcohol co-ingestion adds risk of aspiration.", teaching_points:"1. Partial naloxone response with persistent respiratory depression requires IV access and repeat dosing — naloxone 0.4-2mg IV; BVM ventilation must continue until SpO2 is above 94% regardless of naloxone given. 2. Naloxone half-life is shorter than oxycodone — this patient may re-narcotize during transport; monitor continuously and be prepared to re-dose; alcohol co-ingestion also depresses respirations independently." },
],

bd_hospital: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Regional — interfacility STEMI transfer, 68-year-old male, BP dropping en route to cath lab.", chief_complaint:"STEMI transfer, RV infarction, hypotension developing, IV fluids indicated", scene_description:"You are transporting a 68-year-old inferior STEMI to County General for the cath lab. Two minutes into transport his BP has dropped to 78/48. He is on a heparin drip. He becomes pale and diaphoretic and tells you he feels like he is going to pass out.", patient_info:"68-year-old male, PMH: hypertension, hyperlipidemia, CABG x3 in 2010.", vitals:{bp:"78/48",hr:"52",rr:"20",spo2:"92%",gcs:"14",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Hypotension and bradycardia developing en route. Right-sided STEMI confirmed — RV involvement. JVD present. Lung sounds clear. On heparin drip. IV x2 in place. Deteriorating rapidly.", teaching_points:"1. RV infarction is preload dependent — hypotension responds to IV fluid challenge 250-500mL NS; do NOT give nitroglycerin — it drops preload and can cause cardiovascular collapse in RV infarct. 2. Atropine 0.5mg IV for bradycardia with hemodynamic compromise — contact medical control en route and communicate the change in condition to the receiving cath lab team immediately." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Regional — discharge transport, 84-year-old female, acute delirium with sepsis vital signs, IV access needed.", chief_complaint:"Post-op sepsis presentation, IV access and fluid resuscitation before transport", scene_description:"You are called for a discharge transport of an 84-year-old female post hip replacement who has become acutely confused and febrile. The floor nurse is concerned about sepsis. You must assess, establish IV access, and determine appropriate destination.", patient_info:"84-year-old female, PMH: osteoporosis, hypertension, mild dementia. Post-op day 2.", vitals:{bp:"88/52",hr:"122",rr:"24",spo2:"93%",gcs:"12",temp:"102.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Meets SIRS criteria — febrile, tachycardic, tachypneic, hypotensive. Acute mental status change from morning. SpO2 93%. Post-surgical infection source likely. This is a sepsis presentation, not a routine discharge.", teaching_points:"1. SIRS criteria — two or more of: temp above 38C or below 36C, HR above 90, RR above 20, WBC abnormal; this patient meets all four; communicate sepsis concern and request sepsis protocol activation at the receiving ER. 2. IV access and 30mL/kg NS fluid resuscitation — for this 55kg patient approximately 1,650mL; begin the bolus while packaging; this patient's destination is the ER not home." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Regional ER entrance — complete heart block, transcutaneous pacing indicated, patient collapsing at entrance.", chief_complaint:"Third-degree heart block, hemodynamic compromise, TCP before transfer", scene_description:"A 54-year-old male collapsed at the ER entrance before staff could reach him. Monitor shows complete heart block with a ventricular rate of 38 and BP 80/50. He is diaphoretic with chest pain. Your unit was staged outside. You are first medical contact.", patient_info:"54-year-old male, PMH: unknown per wife still in parking lot.", vitals:{bp:"80/50",hr:"38 complete heart block",rr:"16",spo2:"92%",gcs:"12",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Third-degree heart block with independent P waves and QRS complexes. Bradycardic at 38 bpm. Hypotensive. Diaphoretic chest pain. IV access established. Pacing pads applied.", teaching_points:"1. Transcutaneous pacing for symptomatic complete heart block — atropine has no effect below the AV node; set rate to 70-80 bpm, start milliamps at 60 and increase until electrical capture, confirm mechanical capture with a pulse. 2. IV access with dopamine available as a bridge if TCP fails — dopamine 2-10 mcg/kg/min for refractory bradycardia; contact medical control; facilitate immediate transfer to the ER team once pacing is established." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy Regional — OB floor, postpartum hemorrhage, BP 72/40, IV fluid resuscitation while preparing OR transport.", chief_complaint:"Postpartum hemorrhage, hemorrhagic shock, large bore IV fluid resuscitation", scene_description:"A 32-year-old delivered 2 hours ago and is in hemorrhagic shock from uterine atony. Two nurses are performing bimanual compression. Estimated blood loss is over 1,500mL. You are assisting with IV resuscitation and OR transport. BP 72/40.", patient_info:"32-year-old female, G2P2, vaginal delivery 2 hours ago. PMH: none.", vitals:{bp:"72/40",hr:"152",rr:"28",spo2:"96%",gcs:"10",temp:"98.4°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Uterine atony with hemorrhage. EBL over 1,500mL. BP 72/40 and GCS declining. Two large bore IVs in place. Oxytocin 40 units running in 1L NS. Nurses performing bimanual compression.", teaching_points:"1. Large bore IV x2 with NS wide open — target systolic above 80-90 mmHg as a bridge to OR; communicate your IV access and fluids running to the OR team on arrival. 2. Do not delay transport for additional IV access attempts — if a third IV is needed, IO at the proximal tibia is a fast alternative in a hemodynamically crashing patient." },
],

bd_gasgo: [
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gas and Go — male, partial naloxone response, SpO2 80%, IV access needed.", chief_complaint:"Opioid OD, partial naloxone response, continued respiratory depression", scene_description:"The gas station clerk administered 4mg IN naloxone from a public access kit before EMS arrival. The patient has partially improved but SpO2 remains 80% with inadequate respirations. Fentanyl is suspected. IV access and additional naloxone are needed.", patient_info:"Approximately 35-year-old male, PMH: OUD.", vitals:{bp:"96/60",hr:"68",rr:"8 inadequate",spo2:"80%",gcs:"8",temp:"96.8°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Partial naloxone response — GCS 8, RR 8, SpO2 80%. Still in respiratory failure. Pinpoint pupils partially improved. IV access established. Hypothermic at 96.8°F. Fentanyl suspected — additional naloxone and airway support needed.", teaching_points:"1. Partial naloxone response with persistent respiratory depression requires additional naloxone AND continued airway support — give additional naloxone IV 0.4-2mg while maintaining BVM ventilation; SpO2 of 80% with RR 8 is still respiratory failure regardless of partial improvement. 2. IV access after partial naloxone response allows for a naloxone infusion — 2/3 of the effective reversal dose per hour maintains reversal while fentanyl clears; establishes IV and prevents re-narcotization during transport." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gas and Go — female, 64-year-old, V-fib arrest, one AED shock, epinephrine indicated.", chief_complaint:"V-fib cardiac arrest, one AED shock, ACLS with epinephrine", scene_description:"A 64-year-old female in V-fib cardiac arrest received one AED shock before EMS arrival. CPR is ongoing. V-fib persists on your monitor. IV access established during CPR cycles. Epinephrine and second defibrillation are indicated.", patient_info:"64-year-old female, PMH: unknown per bystanders.", vitals:{bp:"pulseless",hr:"V-fib",rr:"apneic",spo2:"not obtainable",gcs:"3",temp:"unknown"}, pertinent_findings:"Persistent V-fib after one AED shock. CPR ongoing with good quality. IV access right AC established. Epinephrine 1mg IV administered. Second defibrillation delivered per protocol.", teaching_points:"1. Epinephrine 1mg IV after the second defibrillation in V-fib arrest — epinephrine increases coronary perfusion pressure during CPR and makes subsequent defibrillation more likely to succeed; administer every 3-5 minutes throughout the arrest. 2. Amiodarone 300mg IV for V-fib refractory after 3 defibrillation attempts — it is your most powerful antiarrhythmic in cardiac arrest at the AEMT level; have it drawn up before you need it." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gas and Go — male MVC, BG 24 from hypoglycemia, D50 IV, trauma assessment after.", chief_complaint:"MVC from hypoglycemia, BG 24, D50 then trauma assessment", scene_description:"A 44-year-old insulin-dependent diabetic crashed into the gas station canopy after a hypoglycemic episode. BG 24 mg/dL. He is confused and combative from neuroglycopenia. IV access established. D50 will correct the hypoglycemia and allow a proper trauma assessment.", patient_info:"44-year-old male, PMH: Type 1 DM on insulin. Medical alert bracelet.", vitals:{bp:"108/68",hr:"132",rr:"22",spo2:"97%",gcs:"12",temp:"98.6°F"}, pertinent_findings:"BG 24 mg/dL — critical hypoglycemia causing combativeness. Airbag deployment with chest wall tenderness. Cervical precautions applied. IV access established despite combativeness. D50 drawn up. Fire extrication ongoing.", teaching_points:"1. Administer D50 even in a combative patient — neuroglycopenia is causing the combativeness; D50 0.5g/kg IV will correct glucose and combativeness should resolve within 2-3 minutes; treating the hypoglycemia makes all other assessment and treatment possible. 2. BG correction does not rule out concurrent crash injuries — after glucose corrects and the patient calms, perform a full trauma assessment; hypoglycemia caused the crash but the crash may have caused injuries independent of the medical cause." },
  { dispatch_line:"Medic 12, Big Daddy's Gas and Go — 17-year-old female, syncope, 14 weeks pregnant, IV fluids, ectopic concern.", chief_complaint:"Syncope in pregnancy, IV rehydration, ectopic cannot be excluded", scene_description:"A 17-year-old female at 14 weeks gestation syncopized from heat and dehydration. She is alert now but hypotensive and tachycardic. No prenatal care. IV access established. Ectopic pregnancy cannot be excluded without imaging — transport is urgent.", patient_info:"17-year-old female, PMH: none. 14 weeks pregnant, no prenatal care.", vitals:{bp:"88/54",hr:"112",rr:"16",spo2:"99%",gcs:"15",temp:"99.2°F"}, pertinent_findings:"Hypotensive and tachycardic in early second trimester. No prenatal care. Dehydrated from heat and poor oral intake. Ectopic not excluded. IV access established. NS 500mL bolus running. She is alone and does not want to call her parents.", teaching_points:"1. IV fluid resuscitation is appropriate — NS 500mL bolus and reassess; if BP normalizes and the patient feels better, dehydration was likely the primary cause; if BP does not respond to fluids, suspect ectopic pregnancy rupture or other OB emergency and increase transport urgency. 2. Communicate no prenatal care to the ER — this patient is 14 weeks with no OB history; she needs ultrasound confirmation of intrauterine pregnancy and fetal status; ectopic pregnancy at 14 weeks is rare but possible." },
],

};